<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 0026EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CIA-Afghans     09-02 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CIA-Afghans,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Covert Aid Operation Reportedly Removed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Central Intelligence Agency last month
removed the head of its task force directing aid to Afghan
resistance fighters after congressional critics complained about the
handling of the covert arms program, The Washington Post said
Saturday.
   The Post said CIA director William H. Webster decided to remove
the official after congressional supporters ofthe Afhgan resistance
complained to him about a slowdown in the flow of U.S. arms to the
rebels and questioned why arms were still being sent to anti-Western
fundamentalist groups.
   The official was formerly the agency's national intelligence
officer for the Middle East, an analytical job, and had little
experience in the CIA's operations division responsible for
purchasing and the shipping the arms, the newspaper quoted the
critics as saying.
   The Post did not name the official, saying that unnamed senior
CIA officials had asked the newspaper to keep his name confidential.
Webster still has full confidence in the official and the CIA might
use him in the future to work overseas under State Department cover,
the newspaper quoted the senior agency officials as saying..
   Among the critics questioning the shortage of arms being sent to
the Afghan rebels Sens. David Boren, D-Okla., and Robert C. Byrd,
D-W.Va., respectively chairmen of the Senate's intelligence and
appropriations committees.
   Sen. Gordon J. Humphrey, R-N.H., who heads a special Senate task
force on Afghanistan, told the newspaper that the CIA had ``gone to
sleep'' after the last Soviet troops left Afghanistan last February.
   Subsequently, Humphrey said, the supply of U.S. arms to the
rebels declined to half what it was the first half of 1988 at a time
when the Soviet Union was airlifting to the Kabul government massive
new arms shipments.
</TEXT>
