<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--BigBaby     09-02 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Big Baby,0154</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Sues over Injuries From 11{-Pound Baby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who suffered internal
injuries when she gave birth to an 11{-pound boy is suing a hospital
and two doctors, claiming they should have performed a Caesarean
section.
   Wilda S. Smith, 32, says she has undergone reconstructive surgery
and a hysterectomy and lost some bladder and bowel functions. Her
son, Kevin, was delivered without injury on Sept. 1, 1987.
   ``Her insides have been torn apart,'' Geoffrey Fieger, Smith's
attorney, said Thursday. ``She's still going through a lot of pain.''
   Obstetricians Harry Ludwig and Thomas Zima and Mount Clemens
General Hospital, in a suburb of Detroit, are named in Wednesday's
suit, which seeks at least $10,000.
   ``She had an ultrasound, and the doctors should have known how
big the baby was,'' Fieger said.
   William McCandless, attorney for the hospital and physicians,
declined to comment.
</TEXT>
