<FIRST>r w PM-US-Panama Bjt   09-02 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama, Bjt,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Encouraged by Noriega's Growing Isolation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials say they are encouraged by
indications that many Latin American democracies are giving the
diplomatic cold shoulder to the new Panamanian government headed by
a loyal follower of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   At least six of the larger Latin American countries have no
ambassador stationed in Panama. But U.S. officials say some have
been ambiguous about the reasons for not being represented.
   U.S. Ambassador Arthur Davis, a political appointee, left Panama
in May and President Bush said Friday that there are no plans to
send him back.
   Bush said no diplomatic contacts are planned with the new
government headed by President Francisco Rodriguez, a friend of
Noriega since high school who served as government comptroller for
seven years. Noriega will continue to serve as the behind-the-scenes
power in Panama.
   Among the larger Latin American democracies, only Mexico and
Ecuador have ambassadors in Panama, officials said. Among those not
represented at that level are Venezuela, Peru, Uruguay, Colombia,
Brazil, Chile and Argentina.
   The officials, insisting on anonymity, left open the possibility
that the recall of one or more of the ambassadors from these
countries was unrelated to political developments in Panama.
   The administration on Friday used the occasion of the appointment
of an unelected president in Panama to intensify its campaign
against Noriega.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler spoke disdainfully
of Rodriguez, who was named to replace his handpicked predecessor,
President Manuel Solis Palma.
   ``Noriega's latest puppet president is an unknown within Panama,
with no political following, whose chief qualification for the
position seems to have been his longtime friendship with Noriega and
his slavish loyalty to the dictator,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   ``Noriega's naming of a so-called `provisional government' is
completely outside Panama's constitution, and is, in effect, a
thinly disguised coup d'etat.''
   An elected president was to have taken office Friday but
Panamanian authorities threw out the results of the May 7 national
elections. The State Department has said an honest count would have
shown that the anti-Noriega candidate won by a 3-1 margin.
   ``This should have been a proud day for Panamanians and for all
who believe in self-determination and democracy,'' Bush said in a
statement. ``Instead, it is a sad day _ a sad day for Panama and for
the democratic nations of this hemisphere.''
   No new economic sanctions were announced by the administration,
but officials are studying the possibility of tightening sanctions
imposed against Panama last year.
</TEXT>
