<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     09-02 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Troops Kill Two Guerrillas In West Bank, Another Near Lebanese
Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers Saturday shot and killed two
Palestinian ``terrorists'' in the West Bank and earlier killed a
guerrilla in Israel's self-declared security zone in south Lebanon,
the army said.
   Three other Palestinians were captured in the clash early
Saturday in Nablus in the occupied West Bank, the army said. No
further details were available in that incident.
   On Friday, Israeli troops clashed with several guerrillas in
Israel's self-declared security zone in south Lebanon. An army
spokesman said one guerrilla was killed and two escaped.
   Security sources in Lebanon said a fourth gunman may have escaped
after being wounded in the clash.
   Military spokesmen said they did not know which militia the
guerrillas may have belonged to.
   During the fighting, two Soviet-made Katyusha rockets exploded in
northern Israel causing no damage, security sources said. The
rockets were apparently fired from outside the security zone near
the area of the clash.
   The clash occurred before dawn near the village of Beit Yahun,
six miles northwest of the Israeli border, said an Israeli army
spokesman, who requested anonymity in line with military regulations.
   The spokesman said the dead gunman carried a Soviet-made AK-47
assault rifle and large amounts of ammunition and plastic explosives.
   Later, soldiers showed reporters the body of the dead guerrilla,
who was wearing a camouflage uniform. The soldiers also showed three
Kalashnikov assault guns, two of which apparently belonged to the
escaped fighters.
   Israel created the security zone in 1985 as a buffer area after
withdrawing the bulk of its force following a three-year occupation.
