<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 0241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Ford-Emissions     09-02 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford-Emissions,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Automaker to Pay $92,000 Penalty In Settlement With EPA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. will pay the government a
$92,000 penalty for refusing to replace at no cost to its customers
alleged faulty emission control components on its cars.
   While contending that its warranty on the equipment is equal to
those offered by other automakers, Ford agreed Friday to pay the
penalty as part of an out-of-court settlement with the Environmental
Protection Agency.
   EPA last year cited the company for alleged violations of the
Clean Air Act for refusing to replace the components at no cost.
   The agency said it had received 23 complaints, all of which Ford
has agreed to settle. Also, Ford will reimburse about 500 other
vehicle owners who were denied warranty coverage for similar repair
work, EPA said.
   ``We feel that our warranty has been competitive with other
warranties available,'' Ford spokeswoman Joy Stinson said from
Detroit. ``But we have a high regard for the environment, clean air
... and if the EPA feels this additional coverage will assist in
that arena, we are certainly willing to cooperate with them.''
   The Clean Air Act requires motor vehicle manufacturers to design,
build and equip vehicles to comply with federal emissions standards
at the time of sale.
   ``Congress intended the warranty to cover any part which may
cause a vehicle to fail to comply with the federal emissions
standards,'' said William Rosenberg, EPA assistant administrator for
air and radiation. ``If we see a problem, we take action.''
   Warranties must cover emissions hardware for a vehicle's ``useful
life,'' defined as five years or 50,000 miles, the agency said.
   Ford's warranty limited coverage to emission control parts,
excluding other parts that ``significantly affect performance of
emissions components,'' EPA said.
   Among the parts not covered were intake manifolds, carburetors,
spark plugs and cylinders. Ford also excluded from its warranties
repair or replacement of fuel-injector pumps, air-cleaner-duct
valves and motors, ignition models and turbo chargers, all of which
can cause a vehicle to exceed federal emission standards, EPA said.
   The company's 1991 model year warranty will cover the additional
parts, Ms. Stinson said. Also covered will be eligible
emissions-related components that fail for any reason unless the
vehicle has been poorly maintained, improperly used or tampered
with, she said.
   The automaker will notify service personnel of the policy
changes, EPA said.
   Ms. Stinson said she did not know how much the settlement would
cost Ford aside from the penalty.
   Half of Ford's $92,000 payment will go to Colorado State
University for public education projects on clean-air issues such as
the emissions defect warranty, the company said in a statement. The
government will get the rest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
