<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 0250EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AlarBan     09-02 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alar Ban,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government to Ban Alar Residues in Food in 1991</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All foods containing residues of Alar, the
apple preservative that raised a national furor over possible cancer
risks, will be banned as of May 31, 1991, the Environmental
Protection Agency says.
   The agency said Friday that it saw no significant health risks
from eating apples or other food treated with Alar, but the ban is
designed to end use of the chemical in response to widespread public
fears about its safety.
   Uniroyal Chemical Co., the only domestic maker of Alar,
voluntarily agreed in June to take the compound off the market,
although it's still being exported. The company has disputed
laboratory findings that the chemical may cause cancer.
   The EPA reiterated that it plans to announce in January a ban on
the sale and use of Alar after it has received the final results of
several studies on the chemical.
   Until the ban becomes effective, Alar's use is still allowed on
apples, cherries, nectarines, peaches, pears, peanuts, grapes,
tomato transplants and ornamentals.
   But to discourage its use, the EPA said it would begin lowering
the amount of Alar residue permitted on domestic and imported apples
and other fruits Nov. 30, with a further reduction a year later and
a total ban effective May 31, 1991.
   For tomatoes, processed tomatoes, tomato pomace, meat and meat
by-products, milk and eggs, the ban will take effect Nov. 30 with no
phase-in period.
   Alar residues also are found in meat, milk and eggs because farm
animals eat fruit treated with the chemical.
   The EPA estimates that from 5 percent to 15 percent of the U.S.
apple crop is treated with Alar, a growth regulator that improves
the apple's appearance and gives it a longer shelf life.
   The agency said Friday it believes the use of Alar on apples
declined over the summer because of Uniroyal's decision to stop
selling the chemical and a recommendation from the apple growers'
trade association to stop using it.
   Even so, the EPA said, any apples treated with Alar this summer
could fail to meet the new tolerance levels that take effect Nov. 30
and thus could be seized by federal agents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890902-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 0244EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DrugStrategy     09-02 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Strategy,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Faults Some Existing Anti-Narcotics Trafficking Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Criticisms of U.S. foreign policy made by drug
czar William J. Bennett in the draft of his national drug strategy
have been deleted from the final version, an administration source
says.
   The draft of the international section, obtained by The
Associated Press, notes that some Andean nations face economic
instability and political insurgencies that could be made worse by
U.S. pressure to wipe out drug crops.
   ``In certain areas and circumstances, eradication may be the best
and most cost-effective approach to drug crop suppression,'' the
draft says.
   ``In others it can be self-defeating, driving farmers into the
ranks of anti-government insurgency movements, or displacing them to
other areas which cannot be easily reached.''
   The final version of the strategy, to be presented by President
Bush on Tuesday, won't include these statements, the source said.
   ``We thought that would not be an appropriate message to send to
the international community,'' the source said.
   What remains, the source said, is this statement from the draft:
   ``Careful case-by-case consideration must be given to eradication
programs for their potential effect on total country production,
their marginal cost benefit when compared to other counter-drug
programs in the same country or area, and for the political
consequences of their use.''
   The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said: ``That
doesn't cause us any problem, because that's something we would do
anyway. You want to look at eradication as a tool, not as an end in
itself.''
   The Peruvian government faces a threat from Sendero Luminoso
guerrillas, who have virtually taken control of the Upper Huallaga
Valley, the world's primary coca-growing region.
   The Colombian government, meanwhile, is under attack both by the
drug traffickers and the M-19 guerrilla group.
   Administration officials have testified before Congress that the
drug traffickers occasionally work with these guerrilla groups to
protect themselves from the government, but such alliances generally
are those of convenience, motivated by geographical proximity and
joint hostility to the government.
   Of the three main cocaine producing countries _ Peru, Colombia
and Bolivia _ only Bolivia faces no immediate threat from a
guerrilla organization.
   The draft also takes issue with U.S. diplomats' alleged failure
to stress the drug issue, something congressional critics have been
concerned about for years.
   The draft says that if the United States wants to broaden support
for its international counter-drug objectives, a ``vigorous,
coordinated public diplomacy program'' is essential.
   ``The nation's programs in this area are overshadowed by the
absence of importance given the drug issue as a foreign policy
concern,'' the draft strategy says. ``They remain unconvincing. This
situation is in urgent need of revision.''
   The draft also called for greater communication with the Soviet
bloc, including Cuba, on the drug issue.
   ``We must be prepared to share our knowledge and our concern with
the Soviet Union and Eastern European nations and be willing to
engage them in cooperative counter-drug activities,'' the draft
strategy says. ``And we should be prepared to take advantage of
special opportunities provided by other countries with which we may
have minimal or no diplomatic relationships ... to control drug
trafficking.
   ``This could, for example, include Cuba, which might effectively
block rather than facilitate the passage of drug-carrying aircraft
toward the United States,'' the draft says.
   A shortened version of this message remains in the final
strategy, the source said.
   Catherine Shaw, a spokeswoman for the State Department's office
of international narcotics matters, said the department already has
begun working more closely with the Soviet bloc on the anti-drug
issue.
   A letter of agreement with the Soviets signed in January by
then-Secretary of State George Shultz ``opens the door for technical
exchanges,'' Shaw said. ``That would mean we could help train
Soviets, when they seize drugs, to analyze it, exchange information
on cases.''
   The State Department has said it will be willing to work more
closely with Cuba on anti-drug measures only after Cuba proves its
interest in cracking down on the trafficking there, for example, by
seizing shipments of cocaine headed toward the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
