<FIRST>r a PM-Mitchelson-Malpractice     09-02 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mitchelson-Malpractice,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Motion for New Trial and Damages Against Mitchelson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has denied a new trial for a woman who
said palimony attorney Marvin Mitchelson botched her divorce and
coerced her into having sex with him.
   A jury ruled Aug. 3 that Mitchelson had failed to properly manage
Felicia Gordon's 1984 divorce from her former husband, Robert
MacDonald. But the panel refused to award any money to Ms. Gordon,
saying it found no evidence of negligent or outrageous conduct.
   Superior Court Judge Jack Ryburn confirmed that finding without
comment Thursday.
   Ms. Gordon had sought $6 million.
   Ms. Gordon's attorney, Malcolm Ellis, claimed Mitchelson was not
prepared for trial, failed to appear at court proceedings and failed
to gather proper information on MacDonald's worth, estimated at
nearly $10 million. He said Mitchelson appeared in court once to
request a continuance and to present Ms. Gordon with a $250,000 bill.
   Ms. Gordon claimed in the civil suit that Mitchelson had coerced
her into a sexual relationship. She testified that during a visit to
Mitchelson's office, the attorney was wearing a robe with nothing
underneath and ``flashed'' her.
   The famed divorce lawyer denied all of Ms. Gordon's charges and
said she was well-represented by a colleague while he was bedridden
with a neck injury.
   ``It's a vicious, rotten lie,'' Mitchelson testified during the
trial. ``There was no affair. There was no solicitation of sex. She
has the wrong person.''
   Mitchelson had countersued Ms. Gordon for legal fees totaling
$127,716, but in a separate ruling the jury denied the award.
   The celebrity attorney gained fame in the 1970s as the attorney
who originated the term ``palimony'' when he represented Michelle
Triola in her lawsuit against the late actor Lee Marvin.
</TEXT>
