<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 0255EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-PandaBorn     09-02 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panda Born,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zoo Officials Losing Hope That Panda Will Survive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newborn giant panda cub was in grave
condition early today at the National Zoo hospital as veterinarians
and physicians battled to treat a potentially deadly infection,
officials said.
   ``It doesn't look too good at all, I'm sorry to say,'' Zoo
Director Michael Robinson said late Friday.
   ``The condition of the cub has worsened ... and it is now in a
rather grave condition. It has a fever, infection has increased and
we've had to put it in the equivalent of an oxygen tent.''
   Ling-Ling, a giant female panda, gave birth to her fifth cub
Friday morning. All of Ling-Ling's other offspring have died.
   Zoo officials said the 4-ounce female cub, taken from her mother
and placed in an incubator, was suffering from an abundance of white
blood cells and fluid in her lungs.
   Robinson said veterinarians and physicians were treating the cub
with glucose and antibiotics.
   If the cub does survive the immediate crisis, zoo officials may
have to raise her, something they say has never been done. Ling-Ling
may reject the cub if it is kept away too long.
   Several hours after the birth, zoo officials anesthetized
Ling-Ling and took the cub to give her a shot of immunoglobins
extracted from the blood of the father, Hsing-Hsing.
   Previously, officials had been careful not to separate the mother
from her offspring.
   The procedure to ensure a better immune system has been used on
other animals but never on pandas.
   After giving birth, Ling-Ling nurtured the cub by alternately
fondling it with her mouth and cuddling it with her massive arms.
The cub occasionally squealed, which is considered a good sign.
   The 250-pound Ling-Ling and her newborn were monitored through
closed-circuit television. Because Ling-Ling was keeping the tiny
cub pressed close to her body, it was almost impossible to see.
   The cub was born about 90 minutes after volunteers monitoring
Ling-Ling noticed she was having contractions, said zoo spokesman
Mike Morgan. Earlier in the day she was seen gathering more bamboo
in her nest.
   Pandas bear twins about 60 percent of the time, but zoo officials
said there were no immediate indications Ling-Ling was pregnant with
another fetus. Officials said Ling-Ling spontaneously aborted a
fetus in early August.
   The birth was the latest chapter in Ling-Ling's efforts to bear
offspring. In the 17 years that Ling-Ling and Hsing-Hsing have lived
at the zoo, the pair have had a variety of troubles mating and
delivering cubs.
   The first cub was born sickly and died three hours after birth.
In 1984, a second cub was stillborn, and in 1987 Ling-Ling had
twins. The smaller, weaker one died almost immediately and the
second lived about four days before dying of a generalized staph
infection.
   Pandas are endangered species. Fewer than 1,000 have been counted
worldwide.
   Ling-Ling and Hsing-Hsing were given to the United States by the
Chinese government during President Nixon's visit to China in 1972.
   Ling-Ling is a pet name for Chinese girls and refers to the sound
made by the bells they wear on their wrists. Hsing-Hsing (pronounced
shing-shing) refers to the twinkling of a star.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890902-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 0254EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Names     09-02 0867</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0908</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blues harmonica great James Cotton has been
hospitalized and canceled all of his September performances, his
manager said.
   The 54-year-old, three-time Grammy nominee, known for his raw,
powerful, Delta-based blues sound, was to undergo surgery Wednesday,
said his manager, Gordon Kennerly.
   Cotton has been hospitalized for an ``air pocket,'' said
Kennerly, who further characterized the condition as a buildup of
gas in a body cavity. He would not elaborate Friday or say where or
when Cotton was hospitalized.
   Cotton's illness became known after he canceled an appearance
scheduled for Sunday at the Lake Tahoe Starlight Jazz Festival in
California.
   Kennerly said Cotton canceled all September engagements and
indicated later performances also might have to be canceled.
   Cotton, who also sings and plays guitar and drums, is one of the
best-known living blues performers.
   In the 1960s and 1970s, Cotton taught the late Paul Butterfield,
was invited twice to tour with the late Janis Joplin, and recorded
with Johnny Winter and Steve Miller. He ran away from home at age 9
to play with Sonny Boy Williamson and later played with blues greats
such as Howlin' Wolf and Muddy Waters.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Loretta Swit, best known as Maj. ``Hot
Lips'' Houlihan from the long-running ``M-A-S-H'' television series,
was honored with a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.
   A busload of fans who drove by during Friday's ceremony shouted
``We Love Hot Lips!'' and showered the actress with orange balloons.
   ``They have given me a piece of forever,'' Swit said.
   Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley declared Friday ``Loretta Swit
Day'' in honor of the actress, who has worked with other actors to
protect animals.
   ``Now that Loretta's on the street, when all you animal-lovers
walk by, please curb your dogs,'' joked actor and animal activist
Earl Holliman.
   During the 11-year run of ``M-A-S-H,'' Swit received two Emmy
awards and three People's Choice awards.
   She also starred in the television movies ``Friendships, Secrets
and Lies,'' and ``Games Mother Never Taught You,'' and had the lead
role on a Broadway production of Neil Simon's ``Same Time Next
Year.''
   Swit's next project is an ABC Afterschool Special called ``My
Dad's Not Crazy Is He?'' about a schizophrenic father.
 
</TEXT>
