<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 0142EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Panama     09-02 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Government, Same Old Standoff With U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new man wears the presidential sash in
Panama today but the old standoff between the United States and
strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega continues.
   Francisco Rodriguez, a 50-year-old bureaucrat who has served
Panama's rulers for 20 years, was sworn in Friday by the head of the
Supreme Court as the leader of a provisional government.
   The brief televised ceremony was closed to the public and the
press, and Noriega did not attend.
   Rodriguez is Panama's sixth president since Noriega became head
of the Defense Forces in 1983 and, with that, the nation's de facto
ruler. Only one president was elected.
   The opposition, which last year mustered tens of thousands to
demonstrations, was quiet Friday. The day was declared a holiday and
the streets of Panama City were nearly deserted.
   In the only show of discontent, opposition leader Guillermo
Endara said through a spokesman: ``The fact that Gen. Noriega
handpicked another president doesn't change the political situation
of this country.''
   In Washington, reaction to Rodriguez's swearing in was harsh and
disdainful.
   President Bush threatened more sanctions and said the United
States did not recognize the ``illegal regime.'' His aides used
terms like ``puppet president'' and talked of ``rethinking'' the
canal treaties.
   The United States also did not recognize Rodriguez's predecessor,
Manuel Solis Palma, whose term as acting president expired Friday.
   Neither this nor a drug trafficking indictment against Noriega,
nor economic sanctions that have deprived his government of more
than $300 million, have budged the general.
   When the United States called him a drug-dealing dictator, he
seized on nationalist sentiments and claimed a Yankee plot to renege
on the treaties handing over control of the Panana Canal at the end
of the century.
   When international observers said the opposition slate headed by
Endara as the presidential candidate had won the May 7 general
election, the government annulled the balloting.
   The United States now hopes to end the 18-month standoff by a
more direct form of economic pressure.
   ``We can make it illegal for any U.S. firm or individual to deal
with any Panamanian company owned by an associate of Noriega or
Noriega directly,'' said a U.S. official in Panama who asked not to
be identified.
   Noriega is said to have extensive business holdings, and U.S.
officials said they expect to make public a blacklist of scores of
companies owned by Noriega or his associates by early next week.
   Rodriguez and a provisional vice president, Carlos Ozores
Typaldos, 49, were appointed by Panama's Council of State.
   The council said the provisional government might call new
elections if the United States releases Panamanian funds.
   Rodriguez, however, did not mention new elections in a nationwide
televised address Friday night.
   Like Noriega, he blamed Panama's political and economic
predicament on U.S. aggression. But his tone was conciliatory and he
called upon the United States ``to recognize that a policy of
kicking Panama around doesn't work.''
   ``We never have, nor are we, nor do we wish to be enemies of the
United States,'' he said.
</TEXT>
