<FIRST>r a PM-BlueRoom     09-02 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blue Room,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famous New Orleans Hotel Nightclub Closing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fairmont Hotel is closing its Blue Room,
an elegant supper club where Marlene Dietrich, Lena Horne, Ethel
Merman, B.B. King and others performed for more than half a century.
   No formal announcement will be made. The Blue Room simply won't
reopen as scheduled Tuesday after a two-month summer closing, said
hotel spokesman John DeMers.
   Private parties and Sunday brunches will be held in the 300-seat
nightclub, a victim of changing times and changing tastes in
entertainment, said Anton Piringer, executive vice president of the
five-hotel Fairmont chain.
   ``We found ourselves in a position where we were no longer able
to attract the quality entertainers we would very much have liked to
feature,'' he said. ``We were competing with concert halls,
auditoriums and stadiums, where entertainers had an opportunity to
earn many times what we had to offer.'
   DeMers said the Blue Room had been hurt by changing lifestyles.
New Orleans residents aren't as keen as they once were to dress up
and head down to Canal Street after dark. Some recent shows had
audiences of only two people.
   The Fairmont was offering performers $7,000 to $8,000 a week _
far below the $30,000 Ella Fitzgerald commanded, DeMers said, and
weekly losses were as high as $20,000.
   Glenn Miller, Guy Lombardo, the Dorsey brothers and rhumba king
Xavier Cugat played the Blue Room.Joe E. Lewis was a frequent
headliner and Lena Horne observed her 60th birthday with a 1977
engagement. Marlene Dietrich made one of her last public appearances
there in the mid-1970s, retreating between songs to gulp oxygen from
a tank.
   A local dance band called Pilot, which closed July 2, will be the
Blue Room's last act.
</TEXT>
