<FIRST>r w PM-US-Safety     09-02 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Safety,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release at noon EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Workplace Fatalities Seen Higher than in Other Major Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private group said today that a U.S. worker
is 30 times as likely to die on the job as a Swedish worker, but a
federal agency cast doubt on the comparison.
   The study by the National Safe Workplace Institute also said that
Japanese workers were twice as safe on the job as their American
counterparts.
   The organization compared figures on workplace fatalities for
seven major industrial countries: the United States, Sweden, Japan,
West Germany, France, Britain and Italy.
   ``Sweden had the best performance,'' the report said. ``If the
U.S. had that level of success, America would lose 300 men and women
from occupational injuries each year _ not the 10,700 lives that
were lost in 1986.''
   Roy Clason of the federal Occupational Safety and Health
Administration was critical of the report.
   ``If someone slips on the lunchroom floor and breaks his neck, we
count that as a work fatality,'' Clason said. ``I don't know if the
French do that.''
   Joseph A. Kinney, executive director of the institute, said he
derived his figures from the 1988 statistical yearbook of the
International Labor Organization in Geneva, Switzerland. The
Chicago-based institute is funded largely by foundations.
   The figure of 10,700 lives lost in the United States came from
the National Safety Council, another private group in Chicago.
   ``There are no official figures,'' said Sy Holzman, staff
director of the House subcommittee on health and safety. ``That one
is the highest of three unofficial figures.''
   Peg Seminario, who handles health and safety for the AFL-CIO,
said Swedish employers ``spend about 25 times as much on safety per
worker as we do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
