<FIRST>r a PM-Lite     09-02 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lite,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who participated in a triple wedding
during the the Great American Kiss-Off hope baby does not make three
before the contest is over.
   Menette and Jason Knapp, who were among three contestants who
married during the competition Aug. 26, are expecting their first
child Oct. 4.
   Menette Knapp said she recently had her first pre-natal
contraction. But she and her new husband plan to stay in the contest
as long as possible because they need the top $10,000 prize to help
pay the expected $5,000 baby delivery bill.
   ``Financially, winning is a must for us,'' she said during the
21st day of the contest Friday. ``But there's more to the Kiss-Off
than winning. It's definitely brought us much closer together
spiritually.''
   Under the rules of the radio station contest, being held in the
parking lot of the co-sponsor, a furniture company, couples must
kiss for 12 hours a day, between 9 a.m. and 9 p.m., with five-minute
breaks allowed each hour.
