<FIRST>r a PM-CrashRuling Bjt   09-02 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crash Ruling, Bjt,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delta to Appeal Ruling that Blames Crew in 1985 Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA WEISGERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines officials say they will
appeal a ruling that faults the flight crew for a 1985 plane crash
that killed 137 people, including the three-member cockpit crew.
   U.S. District Judge David O. Belew on Friday blamed the crew of
Delta Flight 191 for the crash at Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport, although he acknowledged that air traffic controllers
failed to warn the crew of the severity of weather conditions at the
airport.
   The Atlanta-based airline said the ruling was in conflict with a
recent jury verdict in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., that held Delta
blameless in the accident.
   Delta ``continues to believe that the facts surrounding this case
clearly establish total government responsibility for the tragic
accident,'' the airline said.
   The airline had sought to make the government pay all or part of
the millions of dollars in claims arising from the crash.
   Belew said Delta failed to prove that the two federal agencies
were negligent in the Aug. 2, 1985 crash of the Lockheed L-1011,
which was en route from Fort Lauderdale, Fla. Twenty-seven
passengers survived the crash.
   ``The crew has seen lightning, identified a thunderstorm and has
encountered a performance increase (in air speed),'' Belew said.
``There was no explanation for continuing at this point. Every clue
the crew had received was worse than the previous one.''
   ``This sends a message to Delta Air Lines that the people who
control the operation of aircraft must be held to the highest
standards of care,'' said Roy Krieger, a former government lawyer in
the case who is representing clients suing Delta over the August
1988 crash of a Boeing 727 in Dallas.
   Hal Monk, a Fort Worth attorney representing some of the victims'
families, said, ``From my standpoint, the flight crew made a simple
decision to fly an airplane load of people into a thunderstorm.''
   Delta argued in the 14-month trial that government meteorologists
and air traffic controllers failed to warn the crew of the severity
of the weather. The National Transportation Safety Board ruled that
the crash was caused by wind shear _ a dangerous downdraft of air
associated with severe thunderstorms.
   Delta already has paid $66 million in damages as a result of the
case. In those cases, the plaintiffs waived the liability issue.
Sixteen families are continuing to sue Delta over the crash.
   The government did not escape criticism in Belew's ruling, which
cited the responses of controllers and meteorologists.
   Belew said tower personnel should have made sure that incoming
pilots were aware of weather conditions, and that a meteorologist
should have been sure that the weather was being monitored
continuously while he took a long dinner break.
   But Belew cited other cases in which the controller's failure to
warn pilots of bad weather was not characterized as negligence.
   James Dillman, attorney for the Federal Aviation Administration,
said the controllers would be briefed on the ruling, but that no
formal disciplinary action will be taken.
   In Washington, Joe Friday, assistant administrator for weather
services at the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration,
said: ``We are continuing to work with the FAA and the aviation
industry to improve our science and technology so that this kind of
tragedy will not be repeated.''
   Belew discounted the government contention that Delta had not
adequately trained pilots to handle wind shear situations. He called
Delta's training ``lax'' but not a factor in the accident.
   The judge also ruled out the possibility that tranquilizers Capt.
Edward M. Connors might have been taking at the time of the accident
contributed to the crash.
   Pilot error also was cited as a cause of a Delta crash in 1988,
which killed 14 people. The airline has accepted responsibility for
that crash and fired the flight crew after it was determined that
the flaps were not set in the proper position for takeoff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890902-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 0617EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary     09-02 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Committee Rejects Withdrawing Communist Party From Workplace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party's senior officials
rejected a leading reformer's call to end party activity in the
workplace but said other political groups can also participate, the
official news agency said today.
   The rejection was considered a setback for the reformer, Imre
Pozsgay, who was expected to attend a two-day congress of
like-minded Communists opening today.
   At a party Central Committee meeting Friday, members agreed the
party ``should not interfere with company matters'' the news agency
MTI quoted party spokesman Laszlo Major as saying.
   While the majority of committee members were against complete
withdrawal from the workplace, most agreed ``the opportunity for the
appearance of the other political forces should be made possible,''
Major said.
   A party source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said less
than 20 of the Central Committee's 113 members had been asked to
attend today's meeting of reformers, indicating that less than a
sixth of the party leadership was fully committed to change.
   Pozsgay is the party's candidate for president in elections next
year. The post is being created as part of reforms aimed at creating
a multiparty democracy in Hungary.
   The Central Committee meeting was called in part to review
preparations for a full party congress starting Oct. 6. The meeting
is expected to pit hard-liners against reformers over the party's
future course.
   The reformers have said they will form a social democratic party
unless most of their views are adopted at the meeting. Their demands
include implementation of a market economy.
</TEXT>
