<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 0450EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-UAL Bjt   09-02 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL, Bjt,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor-Managment Bid Offers $6.5 Billion to Control United Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A labor-management proposal to buy UAL Corp. for
$6.5 billion would put the workers in the corporate cockpit of
United Airlines in the nation's largest employee-owned company.
   British Airways would come on board as a minority owner of the
company in an arrangement that would put the heads of each airline
on each other's board of directors.
   While United's directors were pondering the offer of $300 a share
Friday, there were reports that investor Marvin Davis was
considering topping the offer.
   The Machinists union, which has opposed past employee ownership
schemes, did not say whether it plans to join the current venture.
   ``The Machinists are a major issue. ... They're a potential
killer to the deal,'' said Andrew Geller, a financial analyst who
watches the airline industry for Provident National Bank in
Philadelphia.
   UAL directors said Friday they were reviewing the proposal.
Davis, a California investor, started the bidding on the airline and
earlier had made an offer of $275 a share, or $6.19 billion.
   Jim Damron, a spokesman for United's unionized pilots, said there
has been constant contact with the Machinists, but he would not say
if that union had moved any closer to joining an employee-ownership
plan first suggested by pilots in 1987. Telephone calls to the
Machinists offices went unanswered.
   United has more than 70,000 employees, including about 25,000
members of the Machinists union, 6,300 members of the Air Line
Pilots Association and 12,600 flight attendants.
   The flight attendants' union has said it wants to participate in
the deal.
   Mary Conway, a spokeswoman for Davis, said ``he and his advisers
are studying the situation.'' She refused to comment further.
   One industry analyst said he believes the battle for UAL is
``basically a two-horse field'' with the management-employee group
having the edge over Davis.
   ``It would be awfully hard to see someone else come in at this
point and make any money acquiring United without liquidating (the
airline's) assets,'' said Louis A. Marckesano, an analyst with
Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. in Philadelphia.
   Some have suggested that Davis started the bidding war to jack up
the price of United's stock, of which he is a major owner. Others
say Davis really wants to buy the company.
   ``I'm more from the former school,'' said analyst Geller. ``He
could make enormous profits, but we'll know in a few days.''
   UAL stock, which was trading at about $90 a year ago, soared
$13.50 to $166 on July 9 in a buying frenzy on takeover talk. The
price went to $210.75 when Davis put in his first bid and on Friday
it jumped $7.25 and closed at $287 on rumors of the labor-management
offer.
   Under the proposal, British Airways would control 15 percent of
UAL stock. The employees would agree to unspecified wage concessions
in exchange for participation in a stock ownership plan that would
give them 75 percent of the airline.
   UAL Chairman Stephen Wolf said that under the proposal, the
owners did not contemplate selling any essential assets or revising
plans for expanding the airline fleet and routes.
   British Airways said it has agreed in principal to invest $750
million in the consortium. Earlier unconfirmed reports indicated
that the pilots' union might invest as much as $1 billion. The rest
of the buyout funding apparently would be borrowed.
   The largest U.S. company owned by its employees is Avis Inc. An
employee stock ownership plan representing 11,000 Avis workers took
the car rental company private in a $1.75 billion buyout in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
