<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Strike Oklahoma; Rain Dampens New England</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms broke out in humid air in Oklahoma ahead of a cold
front that was slowly pushing southward into the southern Plains and
the lower Mississippi Valley today.
   In Oklahoma County, intense thunderstorm winds snapped off a
utility pole and blew down a tin building Friday night. A man was
injured when several large pieces of wood were thrown into his
mobile home by the wind.
   Strong thunderstorm winds also toppled a large tree and blew a
truck off a road in Canadian County, Okla. Thunderstorms also
produced golf ball-size hail at Shawnee, where winds gusted up to 70
mph. Nearly 4 inches of rain fell at Edmond, Okla.
   Elsewhere, showers, drizzle and fog extended from the middle
Atlantic Coast into New England. Fog also developed over southwest
Kansas and covered much of the eastern Gulf Coast, the southern
Atlantic Coast and Florida.
   An upper air low pressure system off the coast of Washington
state caused showers and some thunderstorms to be scattered from the
Pacific Northwest into the northern Rockies.
   An area of high pressure over North Dakota produced clear skies
and cool temperatures from the upper Great Lakes to the central
Rockies.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included nearly 2{ inches at Vero Beach, Fla., more than 1} inches
at Homestead, Fla., and 1{ inches at McAlester, Okla.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms over
Florida, the eastern Gulf Coast, Arkansas, the Tennessee Valley and
the middle and southern Atlantic Coast; scattered showers and
thunderstorms over eastern New England and the northern Rockies; and
strong winds over parts of the central Rockies.
   Highs were expected to be in the 60s and 70s in New England, the
northern Ohio Valley, the Great Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley,
the northern Rockies and the central and northern Pacific Coast; in
the 100s in the desert Southwest; and in the 80s and 90s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 42
degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 92 degrees at Phoenix and Glendale,
Ariz.
