<FIRST>r a PM-RacialAttack     09-02 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Racial Attack,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Bail for Alleged Gunman After Innocent Plea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge released on bond two alleged members of a
mob involved in the death of a black youth, and angry supporters of
the youth's family clashed with a defense attorney and members of
the news media.
   The alleged ringleader of the mob, Joseph Fama, was ordered held
without bail Friday after he pleaded innocent to charges he shot and
killed 16-year-old Yusuf Hawkins.
   Prosecutors said Fama led the gang of up to 30 whites who
attacked Hawkins and three other black teen-agers in the Bensonhurst
section of Brooklyn on Aug. 23. They said Fama shot Hawkins four
times at close range.
   Fama fled after the shooting and was a fugitive until he
surrendered Thursday to police in Oneonta, 175 miles north of New
York. He was returned to Brooklyn, where witnesses identified him in
a lineup, said Assistant District Attorney Paul Burns.
   Fama's attorney, David A. DePetris, entered an innocent plea on
behalf of his client, charged with murder, assault, criminal
possession of a weapon, menacing, riot and aggravated harassment.
   The killing led to a week of protests and heightened racial
tensions in the city. Hours after Fama was returned to Brooklyn on
Thursday, those at the head of a protest march involving an
estimated 8,000 people clashed with officers at the foot of the
Brooklyn Bridge. Two protesters and 44 officers were injured, police
said.
   Six other Bensonhurst youths have been arrested in the attack,
and two of them _ Keith Mondello, 19, and Pasquale Raucci, 18 _ have
been indicted on murder charges.
   They pleaded innocent at an arraignment Friday and Justice John
J. DeLury allowed Mondello freed on $100,000 bail and Raucci on
$75,000 bail.
   That decision outraged Hawkins' family and their supporters.
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, an adviser to the Hawkins family,
interrupted an interview that reporters were conducting with
Mondello's lawyer, Stephen Murphy, and called him a murderer.
   ``We're going to get you this time, Murphy,'' Sharpton screamed.
``We'll see you tomorrow in Bensonhurst.''
   A few minutes later, outside the courthouse, a Sharpton supporter
attacked a WNYW-TV camera crew that was taping the Hawkins' family.
   Station spokeswoman Barbara Ware said technician Barbara Lloyd
was treated for back injuries and cameraman Nick Jutchenko for
multiple injuries. The two said they would file a complaint against
the attacker.
   New York Newsday photographer Lilliana Nieto also was attacked by
the group while she took photographs of Ms. Lloyd being attacked.
She said Sharpton yelled ``Get her'' and someone smacked her in the
face and head.
   Sharpton later telephoned the television station and apologized
for the attacks.
</TEXT>
