<FIRST>r a PM-DeputiesSuspended     09-02 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deputies Suspended,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>L.A. Sheriff Suspends Nine Veteran Narcotics Officers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAUREN BLAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine longtime members of the sheriff's
narcotics division have been suspended after auditors found cash
missing that was seized in drug raids.
   ``It's the first time anything of this magnitude has been
suspected in this department,'' Sheriff Sherman Block said Friday at
a news conference announcing the suspensions.
   Block refused to say how much money was missing or whether it
disappeared at one time or over several drug busts. No one has been
arrested or charged in the investigation, which is continuing, Block
said.
   The Los Angeles Times today quotes a federal official the
newspaper did not identify as saying: ``We don't know the full
amount of money at this time. It could run into a couple of hundred
thousand dollars.
   ``The money was not getting to the evidence vault. I think they
took a little each time rather than a major amount.''
   FBI agent Lawrence Lawler confirmed the money was missing from
cash confiscated during drug busts, saying, ``It never reached the
evidence locker.'' He would not provide other details.
   The suspensions with pay of the eight deputies and one sergeant,
resulted from a federal investigation prompted by a routine audit in
October 1988, Block said.
   The nine narcotics division members, who worked together as a
team, had spent nine to 22 years with the department.
   ``Since the people work as a team, the entire team was placed in
administrative leave,'' Block said.
   ``Let me assure you that this incident involved a very small
number of the 10,700 dedicated people in the department, '' Block
said. ``Let me also assure you that I will not tolerate the
corruption of even one of the department's members.''
</TEXT>
