<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 0649EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LeeExcommunicated     09-02 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lee Excommunicated,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mormon Church Excommunicates First Indian General Authority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERN ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mormon Church excommunicated the only
Indian to achieve a high position in its hierarchy after he acused
church leaders of racism and said the president was too feeble to
make decisions.
   The excommunication of Elder George P. Lee was announced Friday
in a terse, one-paragraph statement. Lee's excommunication is the
first of a Mormon Church general authority in 46 years.
   The communique said Lee was expelled for ``apostasy and other
conduct unbecoming a member of the church.'' Church spokesman Don
LeFevre would not elaborate on the statement.
   Lee said the action stemmed from basic doctrinal disagreements
with church leaders about the role of American Indians in the
religion and from his contention the leadership is racist,
materialistic and bent on changing the meaning of Mormon scripture.
   ``It got to the point where I had to follow them or Jesus Christ,
and I chose to follow Jesus Christ,'' Lee said in an interview. ``I
told them they are the ones that are apostatizing _ teaching false
doctrine.''
   Lee, 46, was made a member of the First Quorum of the Seventy in
1975. The leadership group is responsible for administering the
affairs of the 6.7 million-member church under the direction of the
Quorum of the Twelve Apostles and the church presidency. Members of
the all-male leadership are known as general authorities.
   In an hourlong meeting with church President Ezra Taft Benson,
Benson's two counselors and the twelve-member quorum, Lee read a
23-page, handwritten letter in which he accused fellow churchmen of
distorting doctrine to satisfy their own racial bias, relegating
Indians to second-class status and denying them their rightful place
in the faith's theology.
   ``While physical extermination may have been one of (the) federal
government's policies long ago ... your current scriptural and
spiritual extermination ... is the greater sin and great shall be
your condemnation for this,'' Lee wrote.
   The church believes American Indians are the descendants of
ancient peoples described in the Book of Mormon, published in 1830
by church founder Joseph Smith.
   Lee said prophesies in the Book of Mormon are clear in defining
Indians and Jews as literal descendants of the House of Israel and
all others as ``gentiles,'' or ``adopted Israel.''
   In recent years, Lee said, general authorities have been
preaching that non-Indian members are literal descendants of
Ephraim, a grandson of Israel in the Old Testament, thereby giving
non-Indian Mormons an excuse to ignore their Indian brothers.
   ``This type of teaching encourages an attitude of superior race,
white supremacy, racist attitude, pride, arrogance, love of power
and no sense of obligation to the poor, needy and afflicted,'' Lee
wrote.
   He questioned whether other general authorities would remain
committed to the church if they were not given membership on
corporate boards, royalties from church books and gifts from
well-to-do friends.
   Lee, a Navajo and former president of the College of Ganado on
the Navajo Reservation, said the shift in church policy toward the
Indians had occurred after the 1985 death of President Spencer W.
Kimball.
   Lee said Benson, 90, was so enfeebled by age that his counselors
in the First Presidency _ Gordon B. Hinckley and Thomas S. Monson _
made all important decisions in his name.
   The last church general authority to be excommunicated was
Richard R. Lyman. He was excommunicated in 1943 for adultery but was
re-baptized 11 years later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890902-0047 </DOCNO>
