<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     09-02 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Kill Three Palestinians, Suspected Collaborator Killed: Arab
Reports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops today fatally shot three
Palestinians in the occupied West Bank, including a teen-age girl,
and the body of a suspected Arab collaborator was found in the
occupied Gaza Strip, Arab reports said.
   The army imposed a curfew in Nablus, where the shootings
occurred, and declared the city a closed military zone.
   An army spokeswoman confirmed two of the deaths and said the army
was checking the report of the teen-age death.
   The deaths would bring to 557 the number of Palestinians killed
by troops or Israeli civilians since the Palestinian uprising began
in December 1987 and 104 killed by fellow Arabs, most for allegedly
collaborating with Israel. Thirty-nine Israelis also have been
killed.
   Arab reports from Nablus said two Palestinians who were wanted by
the army were killed in a predawn clash on the western outskirts of
the city.
   The army spokeswoman said they were killed while planning an
attack and that three others were arrested. She said she could not
release any more details.
   When news of the clash spread in Nablus, a primary point of
unrest during the 20-month uprising in the occupied territories,
student demonstrations broke out, Arab reports said.
   Hundreds of masked youths took to the streets, raising
Palestinian flags in the heart of the city. ``Nablus is boiling and
angry,'' an Arab reporter said.
   The reports said a third Palestinian, Muna Tamaam, 14, was shot
in the heart and killed instantly while participating in one of the
demonstrations. They said at least two people were wounded.
   In the Gaza Strip, a man identified as Abdul Rahman Abu Shaluf
was found dead in Rafah, Arab reports said. The man had been shot,
apparently by Palestinians who suspected he collaborated with Israel.
   At least two others were wounded in clashes with troops in Gaza
today, the reports said.
</TEXT>
