<FIRST>r a PM-MedicalSchoolName     09-02 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medical School Name,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sorenson Asks Return Of $15 Million In University of Utah Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A millionaire who donated $15 million in
stocks to the University of Utah withdrew the donation after the
school said it could not rename its medical college and hospital
after him.
   In a letter Friday to university President Chase Peterson, James
L. Sorenson said he was disappointed with the way the school handled
the controversy that arose after plans to rename the medical
facilities were announced.
   Sorenson said he felt it was ``unfortunate that the university
does not want to take any responsibility for its failure to honor
proposals it conceived when it undertook a prolonged campaign to
recruit the largest philanthropic gift in the history of the state.''
   Sorenson's gift of 250,000 shares of Abbott Laboratories stock,
negotiated with the university over several years, was announced in
May.
   Protests arose, and Peterson said in a letter earlier Friday that
it had become impossible to rename the school and hospital after
Sorenson. Instead, he proposed establishing the J.L. Sorenson
Medical Institute and endowed chairs in Sorenson's name.
   ``It seems to me that the university's desire in recent weeks has
been more to avoid controversy than to find appropriate uses for my
endowment,'' Sorenson wrote in response.
   He said he realized the endowment plan had created ``substantial
pressure'' on the university.
   ``I do not want the siege to continue on my account,'' he said,
adding that he felt the university had, in effect, ``adopted a
`leave it or take it,' attitude.''
   Sorenson, saying the gift was perhaps too large for the school to
handle in one endowment, asked for the return of the stock ``so that
I can reallocate it to other charitable institutions that are in
need.''
   Mike Mattsson, university vice president for development,
apologized for ``the harm caused through all of this to the Sorenson
family and to the university.''
   ``I assume the council will respond to his request and return the
money,'' Mattsson said. ``As I understand the process and release of
the letter, this closes any other options for being explored.''
</TEXT>
