<FIRST>u i PM-Iran 1stLd-Writethru   09-02 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0480,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Quits as Armed Forces Chief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 9th graf pvs, ``Akbar...'' to CORRECT surname to Torkan.
Pickup 10th graf pvs, ``Torkan, a...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hashemi Rafsanjani has resigned
as commander-in-chief of Iran's armed forces, saying he is too busy
with other matters, Tehran Radio reported today.
   Rafsanjani resigned in a letter to Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who
took over as the Islamic republic's spiritual leader after Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini died June 3, the state-run radio said in a report
monitored in Nicosia. Khamenei accepted Rafsanjani's resignation,
the radio said. It gave no other details.
   Khomeini appointed Rafsanjani as commander-in-chief in June 1988
after Iranian forces were defeated by the Iraqis in a series of
offensives in the Persian Gulf war. Rafsanjani's main task was to
reorganize Iran's military, badly demoralized by the battlefield
setbacks and nearly eight years of war.
   The disarray in the fractious military, the shortage of weapons
and growing war weariness among Iran's 50 million people after
horrendous casualties led him instead to persuade Khomeini to
unconditionally accept a 1987 U.N. Security Council cease-fire
resolution. That took effect Aug. 20, 1988.
   The resignation of Ransanjani, 55, as Iran's military chief
indicates he will focus his priorities on his declared policy of
revitalizing Iran's sagging economy and the huge task of post-war
reconstruction.
   Khamenei will presumably now take over as commander-in-chief.
Khamenei, 50, Rafsanjani's political ally, made it clear soon after
he was elected to succeed Khomeini that he intended to control
military affairs.
   Rafsanjani, with wide support in the 350,000-strong Revolutionary
Guards Corps, will retain considerable influence in military affairs.
   During his tenure as commander-in-chief _ he also served as
parliament speaker at the time _ he merged the command structure of
the regular army and the Revolutionary Guards to eliminate parallel
and often conflicting chains of command that seriously hampered
military operations during the gulf war.
   Akbar Torkan, the minister of defense and armed forces logistics
in Rafsanjani's new Cabinet, will wield more control of military
affairs than any of his predecessors following the merger approved
by Parliament in July.
   Torkan, a close Rafsanjani aide, was head of Iran's Defense
Industries Organization during much of the war and was a driving
force behind building it up to produce surface-to-surface missiles
and other weapons to counter a U.S.-led arms embargo. He will now
try to expand the defense industry.
   Rafsanjani's interior minister, Hojatoleslam Abdullah Nouri,
controls internal security forces. He was Khomeini's powerful
representative at Revolutionary Guards headquarters and wields
considerable influence in the corps and is well-placed to counter
any challenge to Rafsanjani, leader of Tehran's so-called
pragmatists, from radical rivals.
   Rafsanjani was elected July 28 with a landslide vote to succeed
Khamenei, president since 1981.
   He was given unprecedented executive powers through
constitutional reforms, aimed at eliminating competing power centers
that have paralyzed the decision-making process, overwhelmingly
approved in a national referendum.
</TEXT>
