<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan     09-02 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Least 30 Rockets Hit Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MACFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 30 rockets slammed into Kabul's
airport and main bazaar today, killing at least two people and
injuring more than six in some of the worst shelling in the capital
this year.
   All flights in and out of Kabul Airport were suspended after more
than 20 rockets hit the area, many falling near the main terminal
building.
   Some passengers fled the building while others sought shelter
under staircases. The incoming flight from New Delhi was diverted
back to India.
   Witnesses said a number of civilians were killed and injured when
the rockets hit houses near the airport, but that could not be
confirmed.
   ``It was really heavy rocketing, really dangerous,'' said George
von Reppert, a camerman for German television trying to depart for
New Delhi. ``It was really shaking the windows.''
   The rocketing started around 9:30 a.m. and continued for more
than three hours. Government forces fired back from the batteries of
rocket launchers stationed around the airport, a joint civilian and
military facility.
   At the main bazaar, a rocket hit a narrow alley of clothing
stores behind the Kartpariwan Mosque at midafternoon.
   Firefighters said at least two people were killed immediately and
six taken to hospitals. Merchants struggled to get heavy boxes full
of winter parkas away from the flames, while leaky hoses sprayed the
entire area with water.
   Kabul has been under rocket attack since late June almost daily,
but the attacks today followed a lull. The government accuses the
Moslem rebels of waging a terror campaign aginst Kabul by killing
civilians. The guerrillas say they only shoot at military targets
and the rest are fired by the government.
   More than 300 people have been killed and 900 injured in the
attacks since June.
</TEXT>
