<FIRST>r a AM-HonestWoman     09-02 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honest Woman,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Rewards Cleaning Woman Who Turned In $100,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman took it upon himself to
reward a cleaning woman who recently stumbled on $100,000 lying
around at a bank and turned the money in.
   Marvin Smith, who owns a building and contracting company, said
he was shocked and a little bit peeved when he read that Nancy
Carroll had received no reward. He gave her $100.
   ``I just admire someone with that much honesty,'' Smith told the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. ``It's easy for someone to be honest and
return $10 _ not $100,000.''
   Ms. Carroll, 49, discovered the cash as she was emptying trash
cans by a teller's booth last month. She called bank security and
told them of her find.
   ``A lot of people are going to think I'm a fool,'' she said.
``I'm happy with myself.''
   Officials said it was the fourth time in four months that she had
found money and returned it.
   But for the $100,000 find, the newspaper said, she received
nothing more than a thank-you letter from the bank's president. And
that letter was sent to the maintenance company for which she is
employed, not to her personally.
   ``I try to reward my employees for their honesty,'' Smith said.
``I was totally shocked that the bank had not rewarded her.''
   Ms. Carroll also was shocked _ when she learned of Smith's
gesture.
   ``I don't believe this. God almighty. Is it real?'' she said.
</TEXT>
