<DOCNO> AP890902-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1105EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Prison     09-02 0858</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Prison,0884</SECOND>
<HEAD>China's Big House: It Isn't Folsom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police with AK-47s stand guard at the gates and
watchtowers. Electricity courses through a wire fence surrounded by
a 15-foot-high brick wall.
   Security is tight at Beijing Prison No. 1, but the real controls
are psychological: two hours of daily ideological study, mandatory
writing of confessions, and the knowledge that even if one fled,
hiding would be difficult in the tightly policed society outside.
   This gray compound on Beijing's Educate the New Street is where
the capital's most serious offenders are sent, and where some of the
more than 2,000 Beijing residents arrested in the June crackdown on
dissent can expect to go.
   ``We haven't received any of those criminals yet,'' Vice Warden
Song Wenpo said, walking past neat whitewashed cells. ``They are
still being investigated, but very likely some will come here.''
   They will join about 2,000 prisoners _ including murderers,
thieves and about 20 ``counter-revolutionaries'' _ who spend their
days making plastic sandals and nylon socks and learning to ``reform
through labor.''
   Clad in blue-and-white uniforms with the word ``prison'' stamped
over the right breast, the inmates work in small prison factories
much like factories outside _ poorly lit, noisy, with aging
machinery and numerous safety hazards.
   Vice Warden Song fell into a hole in the floor that had been
covered with a thin rubber mat. For long, embarrassed minutes he
struggled to free his foot, while an aide whispered that perhaps
he'd best take off his shoe.
   The workshop's women prisoners hid grins. Two clutched each
other, trying to suppress giggles. Finally free, Song called over a
trustee and ordered the hole fixed.
   Physical security inside the prison is light. The guards don't
carry guns, and there are no barriers among the welter of drab
workshops, cellblocks, hospital and office buildings. But with more
than one staffer for every four inmates, supervision is close.
   ``There are some (inmates) who resist reform, resist labor,''
Song said. ``They are punished according to the law.''
   They may get a demerit on their record, or ``criticism and
education'' by their 11 cellmates during daily political study, Song
said.
   Or they may be put in the ``Little Number,'' a cell too small to
lie down fully where the light is never turned off, according to
former prisoner Yang Jing, who said he spent 10 months in the cell.
Song denied such a cell exists.
   Yang spent eight years in Beijing Prison No. 1 for helping print
a reformist magazine during the 1978-79 Democracy Wall movement, one
of the predecessors of this spring's massive student marches.
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping crushed it as he did the
pro-democracy protests in early June.
   Yang's magazine co-editor, Xu Wenli, is still at Prison No. 1 in
his fourth year of solitary confinement. Song said solitude was
``beneficial to (Xu's) individual reform.''
   ``He recognizes some of his problems but I'm afraid there must
still be a process'' of reform, Song said.
   Police and courts have refused comment on the status of students,
intellectuals and workers arrested in this year's movement. Song
said he believes most still are in police detention cells being
investigated.
   Chinese sources say some, including a few prominent
intellectuals, are held in a prison that officially doesn't exist,
Qincheng Prison in Beijing's western suburbs. Others, such as ousted
Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang, are said to be under house arrest.
   There is no limit on detention pending trial, and many of the
protesters may never be tried, according to Pan Shizhao, director of
the Beijing Bar Association's research department.
   He said many likely will be given ``labor education,'' a sentence
that can be handed down by police without a court appearance.
   Pan said the law requires that police notify families within 24
hours of detention and sets a seven-day limit for holding suspects
without charging them. But the New York-based International League
for Human Rights reported to the United Nations that these rights
are often being waived for the recent pro-demoncracy protesters.
   Courts have been ordered to sentence protesters severely, and
even defense lawyers have been urged to ``play an active role in
cracking down'' on the protesters.
   Many protesters shown under arrest on national television were
bruised from beatings. But Song said this rarely happens in his
prison, and that culprits are punished. If prisoners think their
rights are being abused, he said, ``they can come directly to me.''
   Pan, asked if lawyers could intervene to protect prisoner rights,
looked baffled. ``In prison (the convict's) duty is to obey prison
rules,'' he said. ``He is there to reform his thinking.''
   Most do, Song said. Only 5 percent of those released commit
crimes again.
   Those jailed for political activities also usually try to stay
out of trouble. Some released Democracy Wall activists now sell
clothing on the private market. Yang, released in April, said he
planned to paint.
   Democracy Wall activist Ren Wanding, released in 1983, was a rare
exception. He broke a long silence in November to distribute essays
denouncing human rights violations and commemorating Democracy Wall.
   Ren was arrested again in June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
