<DOCNO> AP890902-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1116EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AutoRecalls     09-02 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Recalls,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release 6:30 p.m. EDT, TIME set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Federal Agency Knuckles Under to Industry, Critic Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal agency responsible for correcting
dangerous automobile defects has halted 25 investigations covering
37 million vehicles in the past eight years under industry pressure,
a private watchdog organization charged Saturday.
   Four of the probes were abandoned this year by the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration, according to the Center for
Auto Safety. The center, founded by consumer advocate Ralph Nader,
frequently accuses the government of lax automobile regulation.
   ``They are carrying out a predetermined policy to get the
government off the backs of the car companies,'' said Clarence
Ditlow, the group's executive director. ``Our feeling is the public
is literally riding at risk of death or injury in these 37 million
vehicles.''
   Tim Hurd, spokesman for NHTSA, said Ditlow had issued almost the
same statement three years ago. ``It's not the first time they've
been critical of us and I'm sure it's not the last,'' Hurd said.
   The agency denies the allegations, he said. ``Each of the
investigations referred to was closed for good reason after an
extensive investigation by NHTSA engineers.''
   In each of the 25 aborted investigations, NHTSA had requested
auto manufacturers to conduct safety recalls but was refused,
according to a Center for Auto Safety statement. Each time, the
agency discontinued its probe after being rebuffed, the statement
alleged.
   The vehicles under investigation collectively had experienced
2,176 accidents resulting in 653 injuries, 29 deaths and 106 fires,
it said.
   Ditlow acknowledged NHTSA sometimes stops investigations after
finding insufficient evidence to proceed, but said the cases his
group was targeting should have been pursued further.
   ``We're talking about when an agency writes a letter asking for a
recall and they (the manufacturer) say no and the agency closes the
case out,'' Ditlow said.
   Hurd said NHTSA never stops an investigation because an automaker
refuses to issue a recall. In each case Ditlow mentioned, the agency
decided a recall was not justified, Hurd said.
   This year, the agency has ordered 123 recalls involving 3.6
million vehicles, he said. ``The trend (toward ordering recalls) has
been upward since 1983,'' Hurd said.
   Among the vehicles NHTSA stopped investigating were 456,000 Ford
vans and trucks with dual rear wheels manufactured between 1977 and
1984, despite complaints that the wheels came off, the center said.
   Also, the agency abandoned investigations of 50,000 Thomas Built
buses from 1978 to 1986 that allegedly were susceptible to splitting
apart in crashes and 2 million 1978-82 Chrysler Omni-Horizon K-cars
subject to stalling because of defective carburetor isolator plates,
the center said.
   In each case, deaths and injuries were blamed on the alleged
defects, the group said.
   This year, the center charged, NHTSA prematurely stopped
investigating:
   _ Rear brake lockup in 1.9 million 1981-85 General Motors X-Cars,
for which 518 acidents, 168 injuries and nine deaths were blamed.
   _ Rear brake lockup in 450,000 Ford Mustang-Capris made in 1979,
blamed for 100 accidents, 40 injuries and seven deaths.
   _ Rear brake lockup in 2.7 million 1982-85 General Motors A-Cars,
blamed for 388 accidents, 125 injuries and seven deaths.
   _ Seats falling backward in 5.6 million 1981-86 Ford
Escort-Lynxes, blamed for 43 accidents and 35 injuries. Ford
recalled 80,000 of the affected models in 1984, the center said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890902-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1116EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     09-02 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Accuses United Nations of Interference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Saturday accused a U.N. panel of
``brazenly'' interfering in Chinese affairs by criticizing the June
crackdown on pro-democracy protesters.
   The official Xinhua News Agency also quoted a government
spokesman as saying the crushed movement would never be regarded as
anything but a counterrevolutionary rebellion.
   The U.N. Subcommittee on Prevention of Discrimination and the
Protection of Minorities adopted a resolution Thursday appealing to
China to grant clemency to arrested protesters.
   ``The resolution brazenly interfered in China's internal
affairs,'' China's Foreign Ministry said in a statement read on the
official radio and television.
   China claimed the U.N. resolution was ``engineered and instigated
by a few Western members.''
   It was sponsored by panel members from the United States,
Britain, France, the Netherlands, Norway, Japan, Mexico and the
Philippines.
   The resolution urged the U.N. Human Rights Commission to
investigate the Chinese crackdown. It was the first time that human
rights questions in one of the five U.N. Security Council
member-countries was referred to the commission, the U.N.'s highest
human rights body.
   Xinhua said China ``has all along attached importance to human
rights.''
   However, it said the government was ``driven beyond the limits of
forbearance'' by student protestors who repeatedly occupied
Beijing's Tiananmen Square during seven weeks of protests that began
April 15.
   Troops were called in to put down the protests killing hundreds,
perhaps thousands, of civilians on June 3-4. Since then, thousands
of people have been arrested, and at least 12 people have been
executed for taking part in the protests.
   Xinhua also quoted government spokesman Yuan Mu as saying any
attempts to ``reverse the verdict'' on the movement ``will never
succeed.''
   ``It is absolutely impossible for the case to be redressed,'' he
said, reiterating the official line that the protests sought to
overthrow the government and the ruling Communist Party.
   In an interview in Saturday's China Daily, Education Vice
Minister He Dongchang said China's open-door policy, which includes
sending thousands of students overseas, helped bring about the
democracy movement.
   ``Openness should alternate with closure,'' he said. ``Windows
cannot be opened with no screen to keep flies and worms from coming
in freely.''
   During the past 10 years, 80,000 Chinese students have left to
study abroad, but only one quarter have returned.
   China has announced plans to reduce the amount of time some
students are allowed to stay aboard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
