<DOCNO> AP890902-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1138EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d w AM-Bennett-DC     09-02 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett-DC,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>District of Columbia Officials Say Bennett Lags on Promises to City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. Bennett has yet yet to follow
through on pledges to give special attention to the District of
Columbia's escalating drug problem, district offficials complain as
his national drug control policy is about to be released.
   When Bennett became the Bush administration's drug czar in
January, he praised the city's police department but bluntly said
that Mayor Marion Barry's government wasn't solving the city's drug
problem.
   That criticism was tempered, however, by his promise to make the
district a national ``test case'' for a federal urban drug control
strategy, a plan he had hoped to release within 90 days.
   But nine months and more than 250 killings later, city officials
say they're still alone in fighting the city's drug war.
   ``He hasn't delivered on his promises,'' Barry said at a recent
news conference. ``We haven't seen anything.''
   As the city's murder rate continues to soar, the district's
National Guard division is lending the police department
sophisticated surveillance equipment for use in tracking drug
dealers, but the extra Drug Enforcement Administration agents Barry
requested haven't materialized.
   U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens has hired more than a dozen extra
prosecutors who are specifically charged with handling drug-related
murder cases, but money for extra police and police overtime that
Barry requested from Bennett and Congress hasn't been delivered.
   Portions of Bennett's national plan have been leaked in recent
weeks, but there has been no word on whether the comprehensive
strategy will include any specific help for the nation's capital.
Bennett aides did not return four telephone calls about the plan.
   Over the past several months, Bennett has made no secret of his
disdain for Barry and his government, saying at one point that the
Democratic mayor and other city officials ``aren't doing all they
can'' to battle the city's drug problem. He also said recurring
allegations that Barry himself used drugs haven't helped the
situation.
   But if Barry and Bennett can't seem to work together, the Bush
and Barry administration drug czars might get along better.
   Sterling Tucker, picked by Barry six weeks ago to coordinate the
city's drug battle, favors a low-cost program aimed at getting the
community involved in the drug fight.
   ``He has been very busy meeting with community leaders and
business, trying to enlist their support,'' said Tucker spokeswoman
Cynthia Harris said. ``He hasn't focused heavily on federal
initiatives.''
   But Tucker's plan to formally announce his program was scuttled
amid new allegations this past week that Barry and a convicted drug
dealer used drugs together when Barry visited the man's hotel room
last December. Barry vehemently denies ever having used drugs.
   The National Conference of Mayors has asked Bennett for a
16-point package that stresses interdiction at America's borders and
the destruction of drug crops in Central and South America. The
plan, which has Barry's backing, also calls for more federal funding
for local and federal anti-drug programs and tougher prosecution of
drug dealers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
