<FIRST>r i AM-HoChiMinh     09-02 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ho Chi Minh,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Leaders Falisied Ho Chi Minh's Death Date, Changed Will</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese leaders said they falsified
the date of Ho Chi Minh's death and changed portions of his will,
putting the leader's body on display in a glass mausoleum when his
initial wish was to be cremated.
   Communist Party chief Nguyen Van Linh issued a communique
admitting to ``a number of problems regarding President Ho Chi
Minh's testament and the day on which he died,'' the official Radio
Hanoi said Thursday. A transcript of the broadcast was seen in
Bangkok Friday.
   Ho's last testament recently was published in full for the first
time. It was made public after his death in 1969, but ``owing to the
historical circumstances at the time some facts were not
publicized,'' Linh's communique said.
   One of these was the section that requested he be cremated and
his ashes contained in three earthen pots for the north, the central
and southern parts of the country, it said.
   Instead, authorities asked Ho permission to change that section
of the will, and when he died the body was embalmed and placed in a
glass coffin publicly displayed in a Soviet-style mausoleum in
Hanoi, the communique said.
   The communique said the party leadership ``found it necessary to
preserve the uncle's remains for a long time so that compatriots
nationwide, particularly the southern compatriots and international
friends, might have a chance to visit the uncle.''
   This reflected the party's ``profound sentiments towards the
uncle,'' it said.
   ``It was because of this that we asked the uncle for permission
to revise this point in a way at variance with what he had
instructed,'' it said.
   The communique did not say when Ho was asked permission to change
the portion of the will regarding his cremation, or whether other
changes also were made with his permission.
   The communique said the party also decided to announce that Ho
had died a day later than he did.
   Ho died on Sept. 2. But this was Vietnam's National Day and the
party leadership changed the date ``to prevent the date of Uncle
Ho's death from coinciding with a day of great national rejoicing,''
the communique said.
   It said that in the original version of the will, authorities
also changed a sentence on the war against the United States.
   Ho actually wrote that ``the anti-U.S. war for national salvation
may last for a few years.'' But the officially announced version
read ``the anti-U.S. resistance is likely to drag on'', the
communique said.
   The communique said some paragraphs on national reconstruction
once the communist victory was won also were omitted.
   It said this was because ``when Uncle Ho passed away the
anti-U.S. war of resistance for national salvation was still
difficult and fierce and we had not yet won a final victory.
Therefore it was inappropriate to make public the paragraphs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
