<DOCNO> AP890902-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1142EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Soviet Bjt   09-02 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet, Bjt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agreement Being Prepared on Human Rights, Women's Rights, Worker
Safety</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III and
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze are expected to sign
an agreement at their meeting Sept. 22-23 expanding superpower
cooperation on human rights, administration sources say.
   The memorandum of understanding, now being drafted by federal
agencies, will also outline U.S.-Soviet cooperation on new topics,
such as rule of law, occupational safety and women's issues, said
Bush administration officials who spoke on condition that they not
be further identified.
   The agreement, the result of a Soviet request, is viewed by the
administration as a step toward President Bush's stated goal of
integrating the Soviet Union more deeply into the world community,
the officials said.
   The agenda for the Baker-Shevardnaze meeting, to be held in Grand
Teton National Park in Wyoming, also includes more customary
U.S.-Soviet issues, such as arms control, and regional conflicts in
Africa, Afghanistan, Cambodia and Central America, said State
Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler.
   The discussion is also expected to touch on new areas of
U.S.-Soviet cooperation, such as the fight against terrorism and
drug trafficking, as well as the functioning of the United Nations
and other international organizations, the sources said.
   The meeting is designed to lay the groundwork for a summit
between President Bush and Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev. No
date has been set for a summit, and it was not clear whether one
would be held by year's end.
   A Soviet delegation is due in Washington during the week of Sept.
11 to work on the human rights agreement, which would involve
cooperation by U.S. agencies not usually involved in superpower
relations, such as the Justice Department, the Occupational Safety
and Health Administration and the National Institute of Mental
Health.
   The wider dialogue stems from a request Shevardnadze made of
Baker in Paris on July 28 to expand U.S.-Soviet discussion on human
rights. Deputy Foreign Minister Anatoly Adamshin conducted
preliminary discussions on the expanded dialogue during a visit to
Washington early last month, said the officials.
   ``There is no memorandum yet because individual offices are still
working on their sections,'' said one State Department source.
   The expanded cooperation requested by the Shevardnadze would
include visits to the United States by Soviet miners to learn about
American safety techniques, said a second State Department official,
also speaking on condition of anonymity. Safety was an issue in
strikes by 500,000 Soviet miners in July.
   The Soviets also want to expand cooperation on environmental
issues, widening dialogue that began during the detente era, the
sources said.
   U.S. officials continue to criticize some Soviet human rights
policies, although the tone has changed with Gorbachev's reforms,
which among other things have increased levels of Jewish emigration,
long a point of contention.
   Bush has said that if the Kremlin changes its emigration policies
he may waive portions of a 1974 law that bars trade concessions to
the Soviet Union as long as Jews are restricted from leaving that
country. The law was named after the late Sen. Henry Jackson,
D-Wash., and former Rep. Charles Vanik, D-Ohio.
   Last Friday, the National Conference on Soviet Jewry, which
monitors emigration from the Soviet Union, reported that more Jews
left that country in August than in any month since 1968: 6,756 Jews
last month, surpassing the previous high of 4,746 in October 1979.
   Since January, 33,444 Jews have been allowed to leave the Soviet
Union, and the total for 1989 could surpass the previous high of
51,320 set in the 1979, according to officials of the National
Conference on Soviet Jewry.
   Last year, 18,965 Jews emigrated from the Soviet, up sharply from
the 1987 figure of 8,155 and the 1986 figure of 914, the conference
reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
