<DOCNO> AP890902-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1240EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Fighter     09-02 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Fighter,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan May Develop Own Software for FSX Fighter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan may develop its own computer software for the
FSX fighter jet if the United States refuses to supply it, a Defense
Agency official said Saturday.
   However, the official, speaking on condition of anonymity, denied
a report in the Asahi Shimbun newspaper that the United States
already has refused to provide the software.
   ``The United States has not yet said it won't provide the
software, and we interpret that to mean we can receive it,'' he
said. ``If it doesn't, then we must consider developing it
ourselves.''
   The paper referred to the software as ``the brain of the
fighter.''
   Japan and the United States signed an agreement in November for
joint development of the FSX, the next generation of fighter jet.
   The Japanese originally planned to develop the plane on their
own. The deal for joint development has met staunch opposition in
Congress, where some lawmakers call it a giveaway of American
technology.
