<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-IRA     09-02 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-IRA,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two British Soldiers Wounded in IRA Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUENSTER, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IRA gunmen drove up to a British
military housing complex, asked two soldiers for directions and then
opened fire on them, wounding both, police said Saturday.
   The Irish Republican Army claimed reponsibility in a statement
made by telephone to a news agency in Dublin, Ireland.
   Police in the northwestern city of Muenster, about 110 miles
north of Bonn, said one soldier was in critical condition and the
other was seriously wounded.
   The shooting occurred late Friday in the village of Gremmendorf
near Muenster. It was the fourth attack on a British military
facility in West Germany since June.
   Muenster police spokesman Hans-Jochen Petzold said the soldiers
were walking in civilian clothes in a housing area for British
troops when a car pulled up and its occupants asked in English how
to reach Muenster.
   When the soldiers responded in English, one of the car's
occupants opened fire with an automatic rifle, the spokesman said.
   Pete Brown, a spokesman for the British Rhine Army, said the
soldiers, who are from the Manchester area, belong to the 14th-20th
King's Hussars. He said he could not release their identities for
security reasons.
   The IRA has repeatedly attacked British troops stationed in West
Germany in recent years in an extension of its guerrilla war in
Northern Ireland.
   The guerrilla group is fighting to oust Britain from the province
of Northern Ireland and unite it with the Irish Republic.
   During attacks this summer on British forces in West Germany, one
soldier was killed in Hanover, and two car bombs exploded at British
military housing.
   The IRA claimed responsibility for the fatal attack and is
suspected by police in the other one.
   A third car bomb planted in a soldier's car was found last week
and defused.
</TEXT>
