<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1353EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Journalists     09-02 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Journalists,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Murder, Exile, Persecution Confront Colombian Newsmen</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bombing Saturday of the newspaper El
Espectador demonstrated once again the risks Colombian journalists
face when reporting on the country's cocaine industry.
   Guillermo Cano, the former editor of El Espectador, heads the
list of journalists in Colombia who have died in the fight against
drug traffickers.
   He was assassinated Dec. 17, 1986, while leaving the newspaper
building _ the same one heavily damaged by Saturday's bomb.
Authorities charged Pablo Escobar, the most powerful chief of the
Medellin cocaine cartel, with ordering and planning the slaying.
   Escobar, now in hiding, leads the list of 12 so-called
``extraditables'' _ people wanted on drug-related charges in the
United States.
   Cano wrote fiercely and consistently against the drug
traffickers, and the paper has continued the campaign since his
killing.
   In September 1986, assassins killed veteran anti-drug newsman
Raul Echavarria of the newspaper Occidente in Cali, another large
cocaine-producing city. No one has yet been convicted of the crime.
   Juan Gomez, now mayor of Medellin, the world's No. 1 cocaine
center, fought off a kidnap attempt in 1987 when he was the editor
of the El Colombiano newspaper there. The ``Extraditables'' claimed
responsibility.
   Gomez now is the sole leading Colombian political figure who
proposes negotiating with the drug cartels, a policy adamantly
opposed by President Virgilio Barco and the defense minister, Gen.
Oscar Botero.
   The front-running candidate for president in Colombian elections
set for next May, Luis Carlos Galan, also campaigned on an anti-drug
cartel platform. Drug gangs killed him on Aug. 18.
   Journalist Andres Pastrana left the directorship of an
independently produced Colombian network TV news program to run for
mayor of Bogota, the capital. The ``extraditables'' kidnapped him in
January 1988, but police rescued him a week later and he won the
election.
   In such a dangerous climate, many Colombian journalists have
opted for self-exile.
   They include Daniel Samper, one of the most popular columnists of
El Tiempo of Bogota, the nation's largest paper; and Mauricio Gomez,
the director of the nationally syndicated ``24 Hours'' nightly TV
news program. Both survived assassination attempts by drug gangs.
   News executives and controversial newsmen remaining in Colombia
have adopted elaborate personal security measures, establishing
private intelligence networks, contracting bodyguards and accepting
police protection of their homes.
   The police recently found and deactivated bombs at the Medellin
offices of Caracol and RCN, Colombia's two biggest private radio
networks.
   The ``extraditables'' specifically cite journalists among their
enemies in their proclaimed ``total and absolute war'' against
Colombians who oppose them.
   Still, owners of 25 Colombian newspapers told Barco on Thursday
they give ``full backing'' to recently decreed emergency measures
seeking to confiscate Colombian drug traffickers' fortunes and send
the ``extraditables'' to the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890902-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1433EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Kenya-Adamson     09-02 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kenya-Adamson,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservationist George Adamson Buried at His Kenyan Camp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KORA NATIONAL PARK, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slain conservationist George
Adamson was buried Saturday at this remote game reserve where he and
his wife, ``Born Free'' author Joy Adamson, gained fame for their
work with lions.
   The 83-year-old former game warden was killed by armed bandits on
Aug. 20, nine years after his wife was slain in a wage dispute with
a servant.
   About 60 of Adamson's friends and admirers, including
conservationists, diplomats and actors, traveled to the brief
service in small planes to his simple scrubland camp about 240 miles
east of Nairobi.
   An Anglican priest led the burial procession to the gravesite, a
sandy hillside of acacia trees and bush above the Tana River.
Adamson's brother, Terence, is also buried there.
   Adrian House, chairman of the Elsa Wild Animal Appeal and the
Adamsons' publisher, eulogized Adamson as a man who ``when he feared
death, looked it in the face and didn't flinch.''
   ``Elsa'' is the name of the lion featured in ``Born Free.'' The
Adamsons taught dozens of lions orphaned or born in captivity to
survive in the wild.
   Adamson and two assistants died in a spray of gunfire as they
went to the rescue of another assistant and a house guest who had
been attacked by gunmen near the camp.
   The gunmen, apparently robbers, turned their fire on Adamson when
he tried to run them over in his Land Rover.
   In his eulogy, House challenged the mourners to carry on
Adamson's work.
   He referred to a passage in Adamson's autobiography, ``My Pride
and Joy,'' in which Adamson asks: ``Who will raise their voices,
when mine is carried away in the wind, to plead Kora's case?''
   ``It is up to us, all of us, to share in efforts to answer
George's cry,'' said House.
   Last week, a friend of Adamson, 71-year-old Douglas Collins,
moved to Kora with an assistant to oversee the park, which is home
to about 16 lions Adamson released there.
   Richard Leakey, Kenya's wildlife director, accompanied Adamson's
body in an air force helicopter from Nairobi to Kora National Park.
   In brief comments before Adamson's burial, he pledged Kenya's
commitment to wiping out the violence that has claimed the life of
Adamson and killed three tourists in similar attacks since June.
   ``It will come to an end and we will have peace in our parks,''
he said.
   After a 12-man honor guard from the Department of Wildlife fired
three volleys into the air and game rangers played a trumpet
rendition of ``The Last Post,'' Adamson's simple wooden coffin was
lowered into the ground next to his brother's grave.
   Among those at the service were Sir John Johnson, Britain's high
commissioner in Kenya; and Bill Travers and Virginia McKenna, a
British couple who played the Adamsons in a movie version of ``Born
Free.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
