<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1435EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Storms     09-02 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Storms,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Rescued From Sewer System After Being Swept Away In Storm Rains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for Undated item on the AM-News Advisory.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7-year-old boy swept into a storm sewer
by a rainstorm said it seemed like hours before he was able to get
the attention of a passer-by by screaming through a manhole grate.
   Friday's incident took place during a flood warning when the area
was deluged by as much as 4 inches of rain, officials said.
   Jason Gephart and several other children were playing near a
drainage ditch area that empties into the storm sewer system running
underneath the city, said police Lt. Joe Mink.
   ``My brother was about to fall in,'' Jason said by telephone on
Saturday. ``He accidentally hit me and I went (in).''
   From there Jason said he was ``underwater for about 10 minutes,''
as the swift currents swept him along.
   ``I was sliding ...,'' he said. ``I was hitting my head on top,
and going real fast.''
   The ordeal took about half an hour, but ``it seemed like about
two hours,'' Jason said. The second-grader said during the time he
worried ``I'd never see my mom again.''
   Police said he had traveled about 1,200 feet through a 36-inch
pipe before he spotted a manhole above.
   ``There was this one hole I was trying to climb up and fell
down,'' Jason said. But he had better luck on another manhole.
   ``There was a 13-inch hole; I climbed up it,'' Jason said.
``Somebody was walking to his mom's. I was saying `Help! Help!' I
put my arm up.''
   The passer-by, a teen-ager who was not identified, pulled Jason
from the manhole, officials said.
   Friday's storms dumped up to 8 inches of rain on parts of the
Midwest. High winds damaged about 40 homes in Indiana and spawned
two reported tornados, officials said.
   In Illinois, residents on Saturday repaired damage caused by
thunderstorms that crisscrossed the state Friday, dumping up to 7
inches of rain, causing power outages and thwarting air and road
traffic.
   Three people were injured, none seriously, in Indiana's Pulaski
County. The homes were damaged in Pulaski and neighboring Fulton
County, including one mobile home that was flipped over by strong
winds.
   After his rescue, Jason was taken to Clinton County Hospital,
treated for cuts and bruises and released. His advice to children
playing in storm water is, ``I'll say get away from it, 'cause I
fell in.''
   His stepfather, Michael Lanum, said the family would go to church
Sunday to offer thanks for the boy's rescue.
   ``We never had this much rain. I've been here for 28 years and
haven't seen this much,'' Lanum said. ``They had like a screen or
something over the pipe. I guess it washed away.''
   Mink estimated about 4 inches fell Friday.
   ``You don't know how much I aged by this incident,'' added the
officer, who has a 5-year-old son himself.
   Jason said, ``everybody's been calling to see how I am, that I'm
all right.''
   Frankfort is a town of 15,000 about 40 miles northwest of
Indianapolis in the central part of the state. Pulaski and Fulton
Counties are in the northern part of the state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
