<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1533EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     09-02 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKMAN, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warning signs failed to prevent cars from
hitting moose on western Maine's ``Moose Highway,'' so game wardens
are now resorting to a rotten-egg spray to keep the lumbering
animals at bay.
   A material known as Putrascent has been used with limited success
in Canadian parks to keep deer and moose away from roadways, said
biologist Ronald Joseph of the Maine Warden Service.
   Beginning this week, the spray will be used at six locations
along U.S. Route 201 between this western Maine outpost and the
Canadian border.
   The spray has an egg-compound base that is barely noticeable to
humans, although it repels moose.
   Wardens plan to check the six test sites for moose tracks before
and after Putrascent is used to see how effective the stinky
repellent is, said Joseph. Officials say that moose are so big and
heavy _ 500 to 700 pounds, typically _ that a car hitting one can be
a real danger for the car's occupants.
   Six signs erected along the highway to warn motorists of
potential moose confrontations have had little effect. Joseph said
part of the problem was that they were written in English and not in
French, the language of neighboring Quebec. Another problem was
theft; two of the signs were stolen.
   Many motorists who have hit moose say they thought the moose
warning signs were advertisements for the area, according to Marcia
Seavey, administrator of the Jackman Health Center. Moose River is
between Jackman and the Quebec border, and many local businesses are
named in honor of the moose.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Speaker'' is a powerful Chicago
Democrat with blue eyes, brown hair and the look of an Irish
Republican Army commando. ``The Guv'' is a Republican, nicknamed
``His Tallness,'' seeking a fourth term in office.
   They become locked in a bizarre political chess game after two
supporters of a little-known political extremist stage upset
victories in Illinois' 1986 Democratic primary.
   But the end of this tale lies not in recent history but in a
murder mystery written by a Sangamon State University political
scientist who uses the news of the day and his knowledge of Illinois
politics to shape his paperback detective novels.
   ``As I look at the paper every day I'm discarding or adding to my
mental file things that I could conceivably use,'' says David
Everson, whose third novel, ``Rematch,'' spins a tale of murder and
political intrigue starting with the election upset.
   Though the book is labeled fiction, readers familiar with
Illinois politics will find more than a few parallels with living,
breathing politicians.
   Illinois' Speaker of the House is Michael Madigan, a Chicago
Democrat with brown hair, blue eyes and an Irish ancestry. Gov.
James R. Thompson, a 6-foot-6 Republican, is currently serving his
fourth term.
   Two followers of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche did win
nominations for lieutenant governor and secretary of state in the
1986 Democratic primary. They were quickly disowned by the party and
lost the general election.
   The central character in ``Rematch'' and its predecessors,
``Recount'' and ``Rebound,'' is Robert Miles, a private investigator
who, like his creator, is a jogger with an inordinate fondness for
soft drinks. In ``Rematch,'' Miles investigates the far-right party
which has landed two of its devotees on the Democratic ticket.
   Though his novels often begin with real-life events, Everson
said, ``I never leave it at that. What I do is take that premise
and, like with the characters, exaggerate it ... always thinking of
course that I'm writing a mystery.''
   A fourth book is to be published next year and a fifth is in the
works. But Everson says he's not getting rich off his novels.
   ``The best advice I heard given to beginning mystery writers was,
`Keep your daytime job,''' he said.
</TEXT>
