<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1538EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     09-02 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists Confirm Being Offered More Than Two Ministries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leaders, praising the new
Solidarity prime minister as a ``realist,'' said Saturday they have
been offered more than the two posts already promised them in
Tadeusz Mazowiecki's new government.
   Party chief Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski and Communist parliamentary
leader Marian Orzechowski made the remarks after a morning meeting
with Mazowiecki, who is expected to unveil his new government by
Sept. 10.
   ``Today Premier Mazowiecki presented his (government) concept and
it is in my opinion a realistic concept, such as would be suitable
for our party,'' Rakowski said in an interview on state television
and radio.
   The tone of his remarks appeared to indicate the Communists are
satisfied with their lot in the new government and will not raise
any last-minute objections.
   Rakowski confirmed the party has been offered more than just the
defense and internal affairs portfolios, which control the army and
the police. He would not elaborate on what the posts were.
   Solidarity guaranteed the Communists the first two posts prior to
Mazowiecki's Aug. 24 election as the first non-Communist prime
minister in the Soviet bloc.
   Of Mazowiecki, Rakowski said: ``I think he is a realist. He looks
on the situation in Poland realistically, including the process of
forming the government.''
   In addition to the Communists, Mazowiecki must balance the
interests of Solidarity and his two minor coalition partners, the
United Peasant and Democratic parties.
   There was no immediate statement about Saturday's meeting from
Mazowiecki's office.
   The prime minister has been holding a near-constant series of
talks with various political leaders in the past week on forming the
government, but has generally avoided public comment on them.
   In addition to what they have been promised, the Communists also
want the ministry of foreign affairs. Also, Solidarity parliamentary
leader Bronislaw Geremek has said the Communists should have to take
at least one economic ministry, so they can share responsibility for
unpopular economic reform.
   ``If ... we receive the place in the country and social life
appropriate to our political power, and portfolios which confirm
this place, then the party will have to be active in co-governing
and extend support to steps to lift Poland out of economic and
political crisis,'' Rakowski said.
</TEXT>
