<FIRST>r a AM-Bush     09-02 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Goes Fishing But Catches Nothing, Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Speech, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush went fishing Saturday
but once again came home empty-handed.
   The vacationing president has vowed to break the dry spell before
he returns to Washington on Monday after 20 days at his family's
summer home here.
   The president and Barbara Bush hosted a private picnic Saturday
at the 11-acre Walker's Point compound for White House reporters and
their families.
   Later, Bush planned another crack at the bluefish that have
eluded him despite nearly daily outings since Aug. 16 on his
speedboat Fidelity.
   Bush has passed part of every summer of his life here at this
rustic seaside resort except in 1944, when he was a Navy pilot
fighting World War II.
   Saturday was the 45th anniversary of the day his Navy Avenger
bomber was shot down in the Pacific over Chi Chi Jima. His two
crewmen perished, but a passing American submarine rescued the
20-year-old aviator.
   Ten striking Eastern Airlines pilots picketed along Ocean Avenue
near Bush's residence, asking the president to intervene in their
bitter labor dispute. They wore their black-and-white captains'
uniforms under a blazing sun.
</TEXT>
