<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1600EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest     09-02 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azerbaijani Protesters Rally, Call General Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people rallied in the Azerbaijan
republic on Saturday to demand control of a disputed region that is
also claimed by the neighboring republic of Armenia, an activist
said.
   The activist group People's Front of Azerbaijan staged the rally
and also called for a strike Monday at factories, offices, schools
and businesses throughout the southern republic, said front member
Aiden Amirbekov.
   He said 1 million people turned out for Saturday's rally. Nazim
Ragimov, an independent journalist and activist, said about 500,000
people attended.
   Amirbekov said the protesters are demanding that Moscow lift its
direct control over the Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan. The
region has been the site of clashes between ethnic Armenians and
Azerbaijanis.
   Activists in neighboring Armenia want to annex the region, where
about 75 percent of the population is ethnic Armenian.
   The Kremlin assumed direct control of the region in January in an
attempt to end the dispute.
   In the telephone interview, Amirbekov said Saturday's protesters
jammed Lenin Square in Baku, the Azerbaijani capital, carrying blue,
red and gold Azerbaijan flags and signs demanding an end to
interference by the Kremlin in the republic's affairs.
   During the protest, some people carried signs saying ``Stop
interfering in Azerbaijan's affairs,'' ``Karabakh is aggression
against the sovereignty of Azerbaijan,'' Amirbekov said.
   The rally was peaceful, and authorities made no effort to break
it up, he said.
   Officials at the republic's Interior and Foreign Affairs
ministries, reached by telephone, declined comment on the rally.
Telephones at the official Azerinform news agency did not answer.
   Clashes between Armenians and Azerbaijanis have killed 100 people
and forced hundreds of thousands of people to flee their homes.
   The Azerbaijan People's Front carried out a brief strike in late
August and then called it off to await the government's reaction and
plan a larger walkout.
   The official Tass news agency reported Saturday that the
Azerbaijan government rejected as unconstitutional a declaration of
independence by a council of Armenian activists in Nagorno-Karabakh.
   In its report, Tass said the Presidium of the Azerbaijan Supreme
Soviet, the republic's highest executive body, met after Armenian
activists made their independence declaration in Stepanakert,
Nagorno-Karabakh's biggest city.
   The news agency did not say when the Armenians met.
   The Azerbaijan authorities found the move to be ``an infringement
on government authority and an unconstitutional act'' aimed at
trying to seize power, Tass said.
   In another ethnic dispute, the national Supreme Soviet made a
move apparently designed to meet the demands of ethnic strikers in
the Moldavia republic.
   Tass said the national body formed a committee to study the
political and social situation in Moldavia. Strikers have demanded
such a move.
   The legislature of Moldavia approved legislation Thursday making
Moldavian the official language.
   Ethnic Russians and other Russian-speaking ethnic groups had
demanded that Russian be recognized as a second official language.
Russian-speaking workers have been on strike at 200 enterprises to
protest the language law.
   A man who answered the telephone at strike headquarters in the
Moldavia city of Tiraspol said the national commission was expected
to visit on Monday or Tuesday, and that strikers would decide after
the visit whether to go back to work.
   In the Ukrainian republic, a Moscow activist reported that
thousands of people gathered at rallies to demand stricter residency
requirements in a local election law.
   Anatoly Dotsenko said crowds of up to 50,000 people gathered in
the capital of Kiev, Lvov and Dneprodzerzhinsk, and smaller crowds
rallied elsewhere in protests organized by members of the Congress
of People's Deputies national parliament.
   He said they were demanding that the law impose residency
requirements and drop a section allowing national officials whose
jurisdiction includes the Ukraine to run for its legislature, even
if they live elsewhere.
   The ethnic unrest and intense nationalism sweeping the Soviet
Union has been resulted largely from the greater openness encouraged
by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
