<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan     09-02 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocket Attacks on Capital Kill Up to 46</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MACFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas fired a barrage of rockets
into the capital's airport and main bazaar Saturday, killing as many
as 46 people and injuring dozens of others, officials and state
radio said.
   The Kabul Airport was closed to civilian traffic after 10 people
died in the heaviest attack in a year, including ground workers and
staff of the national airline Ariana, said Naqib Sameer, a
government spokesman. He said at least 22 people were injured.
   Witnesses said one rocket thumped down just 20 yards from the
terminal.
   The attack began at mid-morning and continued sporadically throug
the day. Government forces fired back from multi-barrelled rocket
launchers stationed around the airport, a joint civilian and
military facility.
   President Najib later used the airport to leave for the
non-aligned nations summit in Belgrade, Yugoslavia.
   A trickle of military traffic resumed at mid-afternoon.
   Sameer said four rockets hit the bazaar, sending flames through
the area. State-run Kabul Radio said 36 people were killed and 30
wounded. The broadcast was monitored in Islamabad, Pakistan.
   There were no claims of responsibility. The radio broadcast
blamed ``opposition elements financed by the United States and
Pakistan,'' a reference anti-communist rebels fighting to topple the
ruling Marxist government.
   Sameer said a rocket hit an alley of clothing stores near the
Kabul river, behind the Kartparian Mosque.
   Firefighters emerged with one corpse on a narrow bed of wood.
They held the blood-soaked body in the air for several minutes when
the ambulance door stuck and had to be pried open with a crowbar.
   Smoke clogged the bazaar and spewed out over the city. Merchants
scurried to save box after box of winter parkas from the water
gushing from leaky hoses. Kabul has been under almost daily rocket
attacks since June, but the attacks Saturday followed a three-week
lull.
   More than 300 people have been killed and 900 injured in the
attacks since June.
   In other fighting, Sameer reported government troops locked in
combat with the Pakistani-based mujahadeen rebels near Khost, 18
miles from the border.
   He said the rebels were firing rockets into downtown Khost and
onto the airport five miles from the provincial capital. The
government needs the airport to supply its troops as guerrillas
control the road to the capital.
   In Pakistan, the Mujahedeen Press Agency said the army had failed
to retake Dargi, a military post about 10 miles southeast of Khost.
It said seven soldiers were killed. The Afghan government also
reported seven killled.
   Diplomatic sources said the mujahedeen attack on Khost appeared
to be the most organized in years.
   Sameer said government troops had successfully mopped up guerilla
positions in the southeastern Kandahar province near the towns of
Torkotal, Makwan and Zargargar.
   The rebels, supported by the United States, Pakistan and Saudi
Arabia, have been seeking to overthrow the Soviet-backed government
in Kabul for 10 years.
   The Soviet Union withdrew the bulk of its forces from Afghanistan
after nine years there in February under a U.N.-sponsored accord.
   The guerrillas have failed in their objective of capturing a
provincial capital to name as a seat for their provisional
government.
   They have refused to negotiate with Najib over his plan for a
six-month cease-fire to be followed by elections.
</TEXT>
