<FIRST>u i AM-NorthernIreland     09-02 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Man in Catholic Neighborhood of Belfast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An outlawed Protestant group
claimed its gunmen killed an IRA member in a Roman Catholic
neighborhood Saturday, and police said soldiers killed one of the
attackers and captured the other.
   Relatives of the slain man, identified as Patrick McKenna, denied
claims he belonged to the Irish Republican Army.
   McKenna ran a grocery store, according to Sinn Fein, the legal
political wing of the IRA.
   The Ulster Volunteer force claimed responsibility for the slaying
in a message to a radio station in the British province. It said it
killed McKenna because he was a member of the IRA, a largely Roman
Catholic guerrilla organization that wants to oust the British and
unite Ireland under a socialist government. Loyalists _ generally
Protestants _ support British rule.
   The IRA has taken its fight to continental Europe and struck
against British troops there late Friday.
   IRA gunmen drove up to a British military housing complex in the
West German village of Gremmendorf, asked two soldiers for
directions and then opened fire on them, wounding both, police said
Saturday.
   One soldier was in critical condition and the other was seriously
wounded, said police in nearby Muenster, 110 miles north of Bonn.
   The IRA claimed reponsibility for the attack, the fourth on a
British military facility in West Germany since June.
   In the Belfast slaying, police said two gunmen rode into the
Ardoyne area on a motorcycle at midmorning.
   One man dismounted, shoved shoppers and children aside, and shot
the man, witnesses said.
   ``One of them got off the bike and shot him in the back. He tried
to run away but fell and the man kept on shooting at him,''
according to a woman who said she saw the shooting and spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``The other man on the bike also started
shooting at him.''
   The gunmen were making their getaway when they encountered an
army patrol that killed one of the assailants. The other gunman
surrendered after being wounded, police said. He was hospitalized
with undisclosed injuries.
   The loyalists identified the gunman killed fleeing the scene as
Brian Robinson. They did not identify the captured gunman.
   Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, said the
gunmen were believed to have encountered soldiers working under
cover in an unmarked car.
   Two handguns were recovered, police said.
   Forty-five people have been killed in sectarian violence this
year in Northern Ireland. More than 2,700 people have died in two
decades of strife in the British province.
</TEXT>
