<FIRST>r a AM-WifeAcquitted     09-02 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wife Acquitted,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wife Who Shot Sleeping Husband is Acquitted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who said she shot her sleeping
husband out of fear for her life was acquitted of murder charges by
a jury.
   Janice Mehaffy, 43, had been charged with murder in the Feb. 2
shotgun slaying of her husband, Carl, 45, in their home.
   The innocent verdict Friday night was greeted with a loud shriek
by more than 40 of the woman's friends at Des Moines County District
Court in southeastern Iowa.
   Her attorneys argued that Ms. Mehaffy killed her husband in
self-defense. Prosecutors said she was not in imminent danger when
she pulled the trigger at 6:20 a.m.
   Ms. Mehaffy said she felt calm in the moments right before the
verdict.
   ``I don't know if that's good or bad to say, but I did. I felt
real good. I knew I was innocent. I knew I was going to be alive,''
she said.
   During the trial, defense attorneys argued that Ms. Mehaffy had
developed battered woman's syndrome. During two days of emotional
testimony, Ms. Mehaffy described bouts of abuse at the hands of her
husband during their 22-year marriage.
   Dr. Lenore Walker, a clinical psychologist who has researched the
syndrome and written books on the subject, testified for the
defense. She said that although Mehaffy was asleep, Ms. Mehaffy
still perceived him as a danger and could see no other viable
alternatives.
   Defense lawyers said Mehaffy had planned to kill his wife in the
early morning hours of Feb. 2 if she didn't make a commitment to
come home after separating from him Jan. 14.
   Although Ms. Mehaffy had been living in an apartment with her
daughter, she and her husband spent the night of the shooting at
home together after the daughter suffered injuries in an automobile
accident.
</TEXT>
