<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Baltics     09-02 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Baltics,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politburo Member Attacks Baltic Nationalists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politburo member Yegor K. Ligachev accused Baltic
nationalists Saturday of circulating rumors of discord in the
Kremlin leadership in order to weaken it.
   Ligachev spoke in a 15-minute TV interview broadcast a week after
the Communist Party Central Committee warned Baltic residents that
nationalists were leading them into an abyss.
   He said that while President Mikhail S. Gorbachev patiently
pushes his reforms, people seeking to increase their personal power
are manipulating the country's problems and unfairly attacking the
foundations of Soviet society.
   ``The situation demands some measures be taken but not,
certainly, measures of repression or dictatorship, but first of all
political ones,'' said Ligachev.
   The political situation in the Soviet Union has become more
tense, he said, criticizing party members who are taking part in
strikes and nationalist movements.
   ``All sorts of nationalists and separatists are working very
actively with the purpose of separating the leadership, to weaken
the leadership,'' said Ligachev. ``There are a lot of rumors and
gossip circulating, and all this is not done innocently.''
   As an example, he cited doubts about the source of last week's
tough Central Committee statement.
   Leaders of the grass-roots People's Front movements of Estonia,
Latvia and Lithuania, which are leading the drive for local
sovereignty, have said they think the Central Committee statement
was drafted by a faction of the 251-member body while President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev was on vacation.
   Saturday's statement from Ligachev, widely considered a
conservative force, appeared to be a high-level effort to show party
unity on the matter. Some Baltic activists think he sides with
officials wanting to clamp down on the drive for sovereignty.
   Ligachev defended the Central Committee statement as ``the very
one to create the most favorable conditions for restructuring, and
to speed up its processes.''
   Officials have reported that Gorbachev called Lithuanian
Communist Party officials to warn them the republic had gone too far
in a government commission report saying Lithuania's annexation by
the Soviet Union in 1940 was an ``international crime.''
   Soviet spokesmen also have said Gorbachev took part in drafting
the statement.
</TEXT>
