<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-02 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heat Wave Hits South; Sunny Skies From Midwest to New England</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The South sweltered and the Northwest cooled off Saturday, while
the Midwest and New England enjoyed mostly sunny skies and mild
temperatures.
   A strong high pressure system centered over northwest Illinois
was responsible for the mild weather from the Midwest into New
England.
   Cooler weather spread across the Northwest behind a cold front
extending across the northern Rockies.
   Summer temperatures reigned across the deep South where they
climbed into the 90s from much of Texas across the central Gulf
Coast states to the southern Atlantic coast.
   A record high of 95 degrees for the date was set in Apalachicola,
Fla.
   A band of showers and a few thunderstorms extended from central
and south-central Oklahoma into central Arkansas. More than 3{
inches of rain soaked McAlester, Okla., in 24 hours.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over parts of southern
and west-central Florida and the southern Rockies. Another band of
showers accompanied a cold front eastward across central Montana.
Thunderstorms were beginning to develop over parts of the central
Gulf Coast states.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 51
degrees at Mullan, Idaho, to 101 degrees at Beeville, Texas.
   The nation's low was 29 degrees at Gunnison, Colo., and Truckee,
Calif.
   Sunday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms across
much of Montana and scattered elsewhere across the northern Plains;
thunderstorms from the central Gulf Coast region through Florida,
southern Georgia and the eastern Carolinas; and widely scattered
thunderstorms from southeast Arizona across New Mexico and Oklahoma
into the lower Mississippi Valley.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 80s or low 90s for
most of the nation; the upper 60s and 70s along the Pacific Coast,
from the northern Plateau through the northern high Plains, and from
North Dakota across the Great Lakes to the northern half of the
Atlantic Coast; and the upper 90s to around 100 degrees across much
of Texas and the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
