<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1859EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Empire     09-02 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Empire,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police: No. 2 Drug Baron Owns More Companies Than He Knows</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAROLD OLMOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The reputed No. 2 man in the Medellin
drug cartel owns at least 408 companies including Colombia's top
soccer team _ so many he probably doesn't know exactly what he has,
police said Saturday.
   They disclosed documents to journalists to demonstrate the drug
traffickers' far-reaching involvement in Colombia's economy.
   Police officials told reporters that Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha,
reputed No. 2 in the cartel, owns at least 408 companies
encompassing a variety of businesses from livestock and cars to the
top soccer team the Millonarios, or Millionaires.
   ``This guy probably didn't know exactly what he had. And he's
just one drug lord,'' an astonished police colonel said of Rodriguez
Gacha, who is in hiding.
   Pablo Escobar, reputed chief of the Medellin cartel, ``is
believed to own more, much more,'' the colonel said on condition of
anonymity.
   Escobar is considered the world's richest criminal, he said.
   News reports say Colombian drug lords' properties in the country
are worth as much as $5.5 billion.
   Thousands of Colombians make their living, directly or
indirectly, out of the Medellin organization, whose monthly payroll
a police investigator estimated at $1.5 million.
   It is not immediately clear how the enterprises and Colombia's
economy will be affected by the government's war on the drug lords.
   Police on Aug. 25 seized Rodriguez Gacha's corporate office in
downtown Bogota _ the seventh floor of an impressive 26-story
building with facilities including a heliport.
   A shining bronze plaque identifies Coordinadora Empresarial
Ltda., translated roughly as Business Holdings Ltd., at the floor
entrance.
   The company led Rodriguez Gacha's octopus-like enterprises. It
ran at least 34 subsidiaries which, in turn, dictated to at least 12
subsidiaries of their own. They permeated almost every sector of the
Colombian economy and were based in at least 13 major cities, police
officials said.
   ``The Coordinadora dealt with mountains of money. I have gone
through a bank savings account to which 315 million pesos (about
$800,000) was deposited in just two weeks,'' the police official
said. He would not disclose the account holder or bank's name.
   The conglomerate's financial ability was reflected in
transactions involving soccer players of the Millonarios Club, some
now playing on the national team competing for a slot in the 1990
World Soccer Cup tournament in Italy.
   Millonarios has been national champion for two years.
   Several pages fixed on one of the office walls showed the
bookkeeping cost of players through December 1987: what it cost to
purchase them from other clubs and what their likely value would be
in a sale to another club.
   Arnoldo Iguaran Zuuniga, a Colombian star playing for the
national team, was sold to Millonarios in 1983 for $38,000. The
price tag for the player was $120,000 in 1987.
   Others, like Millonarios star Eduardo Pimentel, had a nominal
bookkeeping cost of a quarter of a cent and a very high sale price
of $125,000.
   Colombian sports writers said actual sale prices are much higher.
   Among books displayed in executive offices of Coordinadora was a
recent Colombian bestseller called ``The Game's Bosses,'' with the
subtitle ``Soccer Players, Slaves or Merchandise?''
   Police authorities said the documents do not imply players are
involved in any cocaine business but that the club definitely was
financed by Rodriguez Gacha.
   The conglomerate owned more than 20 ranches including
``Chihuahua,'' which was seized by the army two weeks ago. The ranch
40 miles from Bogota was believed to be Rodriguez Gacha's
headquarters.
   Rodriguez Gacha, also known by his nickame El Mexicano because of
his passion for the Mexican culture, is one of the 12 alleged drug
traffickers wanted by the United States.
   His 18-year-old son, Freddy Rodriguez, was arrested when the army
seized the ranch. He is not wanted in the United States, but police
believe his father ``will do everything'' to rescue him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
