<FIRST>u i AM-Libya     09-02 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anniversary Celebration Ends with Some Tension</HEAD>
<HEAD>By TERRY LEONARD</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Moammar Gadhafi ended a grand
celebration of his 20 years in power with dancing and sporting
events that lasted into the early hours Saturday.
   There were air shows and a military parade Friday to mark the
aniversary of the Sept. 1, 1969, coup that overthrew pro-Western
King Idris.
   Gadhafi addressed a special session of the General People's
Congress Friday before reviewing the evening parade in Tripoli's
central Green Square.
   In his speech Gadhafi praised ``the people of Panama in
confronting American imperialism'' and said of Israel, ``The Zionist
entity ... must be removed ... Palestine is for Palestinians.''
   He also pledged support for revolutionary movements in Central
America, South Africa and countries around the world.
   The celebrations were attended by at least 19 heads of state.
Western diplomats said their presence reflected Gadhafi's efforts to
end years of international isolation due to his alleged support of
terrorism and Libya's conflicts with its neighbors.
   But the diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said all
did not go smoothly. They suggested that Moroccan King Hassan II
snubbed the Libyan leader and noted a summit of five North African
countries that Gadhafi had hoped to host was not held.
   Hassan skipped the General People's Congress session that opened
the celebrations and then arrived at the nighttime parade 1{ hours
late. He left after 30 minutes, prompting an exodus by other heads
of state.
   But a Moroccan official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the king had not snubbed Gadhafi but was too busy to attend all of
the anniversary events.
   Gadhafi had hoped to preside at a summit with Algeria, Tunisia,
Morocco and Mauritania to discuss forming an economic union. A
Western diplomat said a committee planning the summit suspended its
work because of disagreements over financial matters.
   In Chad, the government announced it will free some Libyan
prisoners as a goodwill gesture to mark Gadhafi's 20-year reign.
   A statement from President Hissene Habre's office in N'Djamena,
made public Friday night by the Chadian Embassy in Paris, did not
specify how many Libyans would be freed or when they would be sent
home.
   Chad is believed to hold about 2,000 Libyan soldiers captured
during years of fighting in northern Chad.
   Libya and Chad signed an agreement Thursday in Algeria to settle
their dispute over the Aouzou Strip, a 45,000-square mile border
region. The pact calls for the release of all prisoners of war held
by both sides.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
