<DOCNO> AP890902-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 1943EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Angola     09-02 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Fighting Reported in Angola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan government soldiers and
U.S.-backed guerrillas are fighting a fierce battle for a rebel-held
town in the southeast of the African country, Portugal's LUSA news
agency reported Saturday.
   Both sides have suffered heavy losses in the battle for Mavinga,
the news agency quoted unidentified Angolan sources as saying.
   Angolan government and rebel officials estimate hundreds of
people have died in the clashes, which follow the breakdown of a
June truce in the 14-year-old civil war.
   In a report from Luanda, the Angolan capital, LUSA said
government advance units have reached the outskirts of Mavinga after
more than a week of heavy fighting.
   The Angolan army lost three Soviet-built MiG-23 jet fighters and
a Gazelle helicopter, the report said.
   It said determined rebel resistance indicates Mavinga holds a
vital strategic position in the defense of the bush headquarters at
Jamba of the rebel National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola.
   However, the Luanda sources said government fighters managed to
cross three rivers regarded as natural barriers to the advance on
Mavinga and are threatening the town, Lusa reported.
   But the rebels' Voice of the Black Rooster radio station had
reported government troops Monday were retreating toward the town of
Cuito Cuanavale, 95 miles northwest of Mavinda.
   LUSA also reported bloody battles in northeastern Lunda Norte
province, where it said three rebel battalions besieged a single
government battalion in the diamond mining center of Cafunfo. It
said about 300 foreign workers, mostly Filipino miners, were
evacuated from Cafunfo.
   President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and rebel chief Jonas Savimbi
signed the truce at an African summit in Gbadolite, Zaire. But the
cease-fire collapsed a week later.
   Sources cited in the LUSA report said the rebels' use of
long-range artillery in the battle for Mavinda shows South Africa
continues to support them, despite pledging to halt aid under
U.S.-sponsored accords signed with Angola and Cuba.
   Under accords in December, South Africa agreed to grant
independence to Angola's southern neighbor, Namibia, and Cuba agreed
to a phased withdrawal of its 50,000 troops supporting the Angolan
government.
   The rebels have been fighting to share government since
Portuguese colonizers hastily withdrew from Angola in 1975, leaving
rival groups to fight for power. The Marxist Popular Movement for
the Liberation of Angola won.
</TEXT>
