<FIRST>r i AM-Switzerland-Music     09-02 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Switzerland-Music,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Pianist Wins Swiss Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VEVEY, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gustav Romero, a 24-year-old virtuoso
from San Diego, won the 1989 Clara Haskil Prize for young classical
pianists, organizers said Saturday.
   An international seven-member jury chose Romero after hearing 43
competitors from some 20 countries in the 10-day event. The prize is
worth $7,500.
   The jury gave honorable mention to Patricia Pagny of France and
Marietta Petkova of Bulgaria, who were also among six finalists
chosen for two tests with the Lausanne Chamber Orchestra.
   Romero was born in San Diego and studied at the Juilliard School
of Music. He has given recitals in Boston, New York and Los Angeles
and appeared as a soloist with the New York Philharmonic and Los
Angeles Philharmonic.
   The prize was founded in 1963 in memory of Clara Haskil, a
Romanian-born pianist who became famous in Paris and Vienna at the
start of the century.
