<FIRST>u i AM-BoatPeople     09-02 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boat People,0535</SECOND>
<UNK>To Transfer Vietnemese Refugees Because of Outbreak of Cholera.</UNK>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 4,000 Vietnamese refugees living on barren
Tai A Chau Island will be transferred next week because of an
outbreak of cholera, the Hong Kong government announced.
   Alistair Asprey, acting secretary for security, told reporters
that the refugees, living in tent camps, will be moved to another
island where living conditions are much better.
   Fighting broke out in another camp early Saturday, and police
said one person was killed and 11 people were injured.
   Five more Vietnamese boat people were confirmed to have been
stricken with cholera on Tai A Chau Friday, bringing to 11 the
number of Vietnamese suffering with the disease, a government
statement said.
   It listed the latest victims as an 8-month-old baby, a man and
three women.
   All of the patients have teen hospitalized are in satisfactory
condition, according to the statement.
   The first case of cholera on Tai A Chau was detected Monday, one
day after rioting erupted on the island when some 1,000 refugees
attacked police following a dispute over rice distribution.
   The case was discovered as authorities moved in to the restore
the health centers and other public facilities damaged during the
rioting.
   More than 55,000 Vietnamese boat people are living in Hong Kong
awaiting resettlement or repatriation. The government began putting
boat people on Tai A Chau Island in June in an emergency measure to
deal with increasing number of refugees arriving in this British
colony.
   It is general procedure for the refugees on Tai A Chau to remain
there for about two weeks for innoculations and health checks and
then be sent to other camps, but the first three cholera patients
had been on the island for a month.
   Cramped living conditions, lack of work and fear of being
returned to their communist homeland have led to frequent bloody
clashes among the refugees and wutg camp guards.
   Police said 46 men were arrested Saturday after about 200 people
battled with clubs, rocks and bottles in the Shek Kong camp that
houses some 7,000 people.
   A police spokesman said a man died from head injuries and four of
the wounded were hospitalized.
   The spokesman said the violence was triggered by a fight Friday
fight involving 40 people and gambling on a volleball game.
   He said some people had placed bets on the match, organized by
the office of the U.N. High Commissioner For Refugees, and whem some
people who lost did not pay fighting ensued and two people were
injured.
   In a brawl Friday involving 30 people at the Lo Wu detention
center, a 19-year-old Vietnamese man was injured and a 23-year-old
man was arrested, police said.
   An estimated 2 million Vietnamese have fled their homeland since
communist forces defeated the U.S.-backed government in South
Vietnam in April 1975. Thousand left within months after the defeat
but the number of refugees is again increasing this year.
   Hong Kong, unable to cope with problem, has said it will begin
sending back to Vietnam those refugees who left for economic reasons
and not because of political persecution.
</TEXT>
