<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 2105EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary     09-02 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Urges Non-Reformers to Leave Communist Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Miklos Nemeth on Saturday urged
communists burdened with past mistakes to leave the party, saying
those who cannot accept reform should feel free to form new
political parties.
   Also Saturday, orthodox Marxist Ferenc Berenyi was quoted as
saying his Munnich Ferenc Society, a Communist Party faction, is not
seeking a split. ``But we will become a party if necessary,'' he was
quoted as saying by the Nepszabadsag party daily.
   Reformist communists meanwhile published a letter drafted for the
Communist Party's Oct. 6 congress urging a break with traditional
communism and calling it a ``historical dead end.''
   The different factions are laying down their positions in
preparation for the congress. Nemeth warned a failure at the
congress to transform the party into an entity with broad appeal
``would result in unforseeable consequences.''
   After more than four decades of single-party rule, the communist
leadership in February endorsed the concept of multiparty democracy
and agreed to hold free elections by June. In recent months, dozens
of opposition political groups and clubs have been allowed to form.
   These and other changes have put Hungary in the forefront of
economic and political reform in the Soviet bloc, creating tension
with some neighbors that cling to traditional and rigid Marxist
systems.
   Reformists also have run into opposition at home, with orthodox
Marxists challenging their concepts.
   Partly because of the infighting, the party's strength has
diminished.
   Central Committee Secretary Gyoergy Fejti told a Saturday rally
at Fonyodliget, 90 miles southwest of Budapest, that an average of
10,000 members a month have left the party in recent months, while
it is attracting less than 200 new members a month.
   Fejti said 750,000 of the country's 10 million people now are
party members, the official MTI news agency reported.
   Decisions reached Friday by a meeting of the 113-member Central
Committee reflect the conflicting positions of senior party
officials.
   While rejecting a call by leading reformer Imre Pozsgay to
depoliticize the work place by dismantling communist political
organizations there, committee members agreed to open factories to
other parties.
   Nemeth, who along with Pozsgay is part of the four-member party
leadership, was considered sympathetic to reformists even before he
declared his support Saturday.
   He suggested those with ``ancient Bolshevik concepts ... (who)
cannot accept the necessity of radical changes ... form alliances
with those circles espousing far-left concepts and practices.''
   ``We cannot complete the work of the (October) congress with
people who are burdened with different mistakes and who are not
clean ... let us allow them to form other parties, and let us allow
them to leave in a civilized way,'' Nemeth declared.
   Responding to questions from reporters before the dinner, Nemeth
said he could conceive of a coalition of communist and non-communist
parties after the election.
</TEXT>
