<FIRST>u i AM-SudanRelief     09-02 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan Relief,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudan Relief Effort Hailed as Success</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. emergency relief program for
southern Sudan has been a success but more aid would be needed next
year, the head of the operation said Saturday night.
   ``It's clear that there will be no repetition of the large scale
disaster'' of last year, when an estimated 250,000 people died, the
U.N. official, James Grant, told a news conference. ``The operation
is well on the road to accomplishing its purpose.''
   Grant said 94,000 tons of food, including 2 tons of medicine,
seeds and other non-food supplies, had been delivered to
distribution centers by the end of August.
   Operation Lifeline Sudan was launched in March with the aim of
providing 100,000 tons of food and other supplies to avert experts'
predictions of 100,000 deaths from starvation in the war-torn
southern half of Sudan.
   The famine in 1988 has been induced by the country's 6-year-old
civil war. Grant said this year's relief operation has cost $200
million so far, and another $10 million to $20 million will be
needed to see it through November. He said a program of equal size
will be required next year.
</TEXT>
