<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 2249EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SovietJews     09-02 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Jews,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: U.S. Considering Denying Refugee Status to Soviet Jews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, together with several
federal agencies, has drafted plans to make large numbers of Soviet
Jews ineligible to enter the United States as refugees, according to
a published report.
   Under a State Department plan, Soviet Jews who have no relatives
or other ties to the United States would become ineligible for
admission as refugees, the New York Times reported in its Sunday
editions.
   At least half of Soviet Jewish applicants are in that category.
   One result of the proposal would be to encourage the rejected
applicants to go to Israel, a move Israeli officials would welcome,
the Times reported.
   Citing confidential State Department documents, the Times
reported that U.S. officials hope there will be ``direct charter
flights to Israel'' from Moscow for Soviet Jews who would be
ineligible to settle in America under the proposed guidelines.
   The United States for years has allowed Soviet Jews to choose
their destinations upon leaving the Soviet Union.
   But Bush administration officials say the United States no longer
can accommodate all of those who want to come here, the Times
reported. The paper said the administration is taking that posture
because of economic burdens it would impose on the government in
addition to the difficulty in proving that the Jews are political or
religious refugees.
   Soviet Jewish emigration jumped from 8,155 in 1987 to 18,965 last
year and is expected to exceed 48,000 this year, the Times said.
   The plan was developed secretly by a group of officials from the
Central Intelligence Agency, the FBI, the State Department and the
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   Israeli officials said they welcomed the prospect that the
tighter U.S. restrictions would result in more Soviet Jews going to
Israel, the paper said. In addition, Israeli officials said an
influx of Soviet Jews would strengthen Israel, the Times said.
   While the administration is moving to restrict the influx of
Soviet Jews, Congress has moved in the opposite direction. Both
houses of Congress have approved bills that would make it easier for
Soviet Jews and evangelical Christians to come to the United States
as refugees.
   The Bush administration opposes the bills, saying they would
create large numbers of refugees who would impose large costs on the
government.
   Some American and Israeli officials say the persecution of Jews
in the Soviet Union has lessened under President Mikhail Gorbachev.
But many members of Congress and some American Jewish groups say
Gorbachev's openness policies have also given new life to
anti-Semitic groups.
   The administration's plan is causing debate among Jewish groups.
   Some groups say the United States has an obligation to admit
Soviet Jews after demanding for more than 15 years that Moscow let
them leave.
   ``We don't want to collaborate with the U.S. government on a
selection plan that bars Soviet Jews without close relatives in the
United States because that would disqualify some leaders of the
Soviet emigration movement,'' Pamela B. Cohen, president of the
Union of Councils for Soviet Jews, told the Times.
   But David A. Harris, Washington representative of the American
Jewish Committee, told the paper, ``A growing number of American
Jews are coming to believe that limits on refugee entry to the
United States would not be so terrible if they result in greater
voluntary migration to Israel.''
   Most of the administration's plan is subject to approval by Bush,
Secretary of State James Baker 3d and Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh, who supervises the INS and the FBI.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
