<FIRST>r a AM-PipelineExplosion     09-02 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pipeline Explosion,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>NTSB Wraps Up Hearing on Train Derailment, Pipeline Explosion</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. _ A week of testimony failed to establish
a link between a deadly train derailment and a pipeline explosion
here, although federal officials have said they believe the crash's
impact led to the blast.
   Four people were killed May 12 when a runaway Southern Pacific
General freight train jumped the tracks and smashed into dozens of
homes in a San Bernardino neighborhood. Two people died and 31 were
injured in the pipeline explosion May 25.
   But testimony from 33 witnesses last week could not establish a
causal link between the derailment and the explosion, said Lee V.
Dickinson, chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board
panel that concluded its five-day hearings Friday.
   Investigators have said they believe either the impact of the
train accident or heavy equipment used to clean up debris from it
weakened the buried pipeline near the tracks, ultimately causing it
to explode.
   Dickinson also said that confusion and a lack of communication
between fire and safety officials hampered an inspection of the
pipeline after the derailment.
   ``The time of the accident, it's not the time to introduce
yourself,'' he said.
   City Fire Department personnel were not sure what state officials
were supposed to do after the train wreck, according to James Waite,
acting chief of the Pipeline Safety Division of the state Fire
Marshal's Office.
   On Thursday, Southern Pacific General Manager Lloyd Simpson
testified he believed that the pipeline had been fully examined when
he signed an agreement taking responsibility for the inspection.
   The agreement, signed by Simpson and San Bernardino City Attorney
James Penman, said Southern Pacific would be responsible for fully
exposing the section of pipeline near the train wreck. The city Fire
Department then was to examine the line.
   But James Knight, deputy chief of the San Bernardino Fire
Department, told the board on Monday that he had recommended to
David Andries of the Calnev Pipe Line Co. that the line at the
accident scene be entirely uncovered and examined for damage.
   Knight said he released the accident site to Calnev crews on May
15 assuming that the inspection would be conducted. Calnev resumed
pumping gasoline through the line the next day.
   Andries, Calnev's manager of operations, said the firm only
uncovered the line at four points where it was thought there may
have been damage.
   Another Calnev official had testified that inspection was
sufficient to determine whether further inspection of the line was
needed. The pipeline supplies about 90 percent of Las Vegas' gas.
   Dickinson said the NTSB would issue a final report next spring.
</TEXT>
