<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 2215EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Sudan     09-02 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deposed Vice President Sentenced to 40 Years in Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military tribunal convicted ousted Vice
President Idris Banna of corruption Saturday and sentenced him to 40
years in jail in the first trial of more than 30 politicians
arrested in a June coup.
   The tribunal said Banna would serve only half his sentence and
gave him a week to appeal the sentence to a higher military court.
   Banna was vice president of the governing five-man Supreme
Council until Lt. Gen. Omar Hassan Ahmed el-Bashir ousted the
elected government of Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi on June 30.
   The military government has detained el-Mahdi and more than 30 of
his advisers and says they will be tried for corruption.
   After the coup, state television showed films of authorities
seizing Banna's warehouses and finding thousands of cans of tomato
paste, articles of clothes and other items given by neighbouring
countries as emergency aid after August 1988 floods.
   At least 96 people died in floods that left millions homeless and
thousands without food.
   Tribunal Judge Abdul-Wahab Ahmed Osman, an army colonel, said the
tribunal is confiscating all Banna's property, but he did not say
what would happen to it.
   He said Banna was given 20 years in prison for subverting the
national economy, 10 years for squandering public funds and 10 years
for illegally making personal use of emergency aid that poured into
Sudan following the floods.
   Banna pleaded innocent.
   At the trial's first session Aug. 12, the tribunal turned down
Banna's request to be set free on bail to gather proof of his
innocence. In protest, Banna refused to participate in any of the
court's three hearings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
