<DOCNO> AP890902-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 2301EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DrugSeizures     09-02 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Seizures,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Concealed in Truck; Marijuana Found on Boat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Columbia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents found 824 pounds of cocaine
concealed in a truck shipped from Honduras and 23,000 pounds of
marijuana was seized on a fishing boat with the help of the British
Navy, officials said Saturday.
   Customs Service agents found a 2-foot-deep false wall Friday near
the cab of a truck that arrived in the Port of Tampa aboard the
Honduran-registered cargo vessel Carib Haven, spokesman Michael
Sheehan said.
   He estimated the cocaine was worth about $5.6 million wholesale.
   Sheehan would not say who was scheduled to take delivery of the
truck but said Customs was working with the vessel's owners in its
investigation.
   In Key West, a 65-foot fishing boat was escorted to shore
Saturday after 23,000 pounds of marijuana was found aboard, said Lt.
Cmdr. Jeff Karonis.
   The U.S.-registered boat was intercepted by a Coast Guard cutter
Wednesday off Mexico's Yucatan peninsula about 500 miles southwest
of Miami, he said.
   Two British Navy vessels tracked the boat while the cutter
approached. The British Navy does not participate in anti-drug
operations in the region and was in the tropical waters only as part
of a routine patrol, Karonis said.
   Two U.S. citizens and a Colombian were taken into custody.
</TEXT>
