<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 2305EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Motorcycle-TruckCrash     09-02 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Motorcycle-Truck Crash,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Truck-Motorcycle Accident Kills Five</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLACERVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flatbed truck crashed into a line of
motorcycles on a mountain road Saturday, killing five people and
injuring five, three of them critically, officials said.
   The driver of the one-ton flatbed truck, which was carrying a
load of wood, braked and slid before overturning and colliding with
at least five motorcycles on a Sierra Nevada highway at 1:25 p.m,
said California Highway Patrol Sgt. Rob Yates. All vehicles were
immediately engulfed in flames.
   ``Most of them were burned pretty severely, although we don't
know the exact cause of death,'' said Yates. ``It could've been the
impact.''
   Julie Miller, a spokeswoman for Marshall Hospital near
Placerville, said altogether there were about 40 motorcyclists in
the group who were on a trip to the Sierra Nevada for a Labor Day
festival.
   A team of CHP investigators is working to determine the cause of
the accident, Yates said.
   ``Obviously, somebody was on the wrong side of the road,'' Yates
said.
   The 24-year-old truck driver, Daniel DeWater of Shingle Springs,
suffered burns over 30 percent of his body and was in critical
condition, according to a spokeswoman at University Medical Center
in Sacramento. She did not identify herself.
   Two motorcyclists also were listed in critical condition in the
hospital's burn unit, where all three had been air-lifted. All
suffered second- and third-degree burns.
   The names and hometowns of the dead and the other injured victims
at the medical center were not released, but the injured included a
woman with burns over 90 percent of her body and a man with burns
over 60 percent of his body.
   Two other motorcyclists were treated at Marshall Hospital; one
was released and another was in stable condition, Miller said.
   The rural highway is in a heavily-forested area and is a private
U.S. Forest Service road that is open to the public, Yates said,
adding that it is well-maintained, paved and painted.
   The fire touched off a small brush fire that was quickly
controlled, Yates said.
</TEXT>
