<FIRST>u i AM-China-Fares     09-02 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Fares,0217</SECOND>
<UNK>China Doubles Fares On Transportation System</UNK>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passenger fares on Chinese trains, planes and
ships will roughly double as of Tuesday, providing additional funds
for the crowded transportation system and new burdens for
inflation-hit users.
   Government spokesman Yuan Mu, in an announcement reported in the
official press Sunday, said the price increases will pay for
renovations and expansion of the transportation system.
   Yuan said train tickets will go up from the equivalent of a half
cent per person per kilometer (0.62 U.S. miles) to at least one cent.
   A lower-class sleeping berth from Beijing to Canton, 1,200 miles
to the south, has cost the equivalent of $16. A factory worker
receives an average $27 per month.
   Yuan said prices will increase by 77 percent for domestic air
flights but airline fares for foreigners will remain unchanged this
year.
   Eventually, however, foreigners and overseas Chinese also will
pay fare boosts, with prices for all transportation for visitors set
at 70 percent above what Chinese passengers pay, according to the
announcement. That is the same price ratio used under the old system.
   Inflation is running at a rate of 25 percent, down from a high of
36 percent last year but still above acceptable levels for China's
communist economy.
</TEXT>
