<FIRST>u w AM-PandaBorn 1stLd-Writethru a0541 09-02 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panda Born, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0541,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zoo Officials Heartened As Panda Cub Stabilizes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with cub stabilized, edits throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GINSBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The condition of a newborn giant panda cub,
clinging to life in an incubator at the National Zoo on Saturday,
worsened but finally stabilized as the tiny bear battles a serious
infection that claimed the lives of four other cubs born there,
officials said.
   ``The fact that she stopped declining is something we should
cling to for hope,'' said Michael H. Robinson, director of the
National Zoo. ``She was going down and we stopped it.''
   Robinson said the cub's condition worsened during the day, and
``it is now in a rather grave condition. It has a fever, infection
has increased and we've had to put it in the equivalent of an oxygen
tent.''
   Ling-Ling, a giant female panda, gave birth to the 4-ounce female
cub Friday morning in the Panda House at the zoo. The cub is
Ling-Ling's fifth. If it survives, it will be the first panda cub
successfully bred in a U.S. zoo.
   Zoo officials said the cub remains in a special incubator, tended
by doctors from both local veterinarian hospitals and Children's
Hospital in Washington.
   The cub's treatment is much like the care a seriously ill newborn
child would receive, officials said. The cub suffers from a high
white blood cell count and fluid in its lungs.
   Doctors said Ling-Ling is suffering from an infection and passed
the ailment onto her cub either before or during birth.
   Officials are treating the panda with glucose and antibiotics. A
tiny tube pumps nutrients directly into the cub's stomach.
   ``We've had help from a local hospital and our veterinarians are
working hard now to try and get the infection into remission and
hopefully to push it over into recovery,'' he said. However, he
said, ``It doesn't look too good at all, I'm sorry to say.''
   If the cub does survive immediate danger, zoo officials may have
to raise it away from its mother if she is not returned soon,
officials said. There is a chance the cub may be rejected by its
mother if it is kept too long. Authorities say a panda cub has never
been successfully raised by humans.
   Several hours after the birth, zoo officials anesthetized
Ling-Ling and took the cub to give her a shot of immunoglobulins
extracted from the blood of the father, Hsing-Hsing. Previously,
officials had been careful not to separate the mother from her
offspring.
   ``This really does show that our decision to remove the baby from
Ling-Ling was a correct one,'' Robinson said. ``If we hadn't done
that, we wouldn't have detected the infection and it would have had
no opportunity at all to survive. This way, at least we have a
fighting chance.''
   Ling-Ling and Hsing-Hsing were given to the United States by the
Chinese government during President Nixon's visit to China in 1972.
Since that time they have mated on numerous occasions, but Ling-Ling
has only given birth four times _ including a set of twins in 1987.
   One of the cubs was born stillborn and the other three _
including both of the twins _ died shortly after birth. Ling-Ling's
longest-lived cub, one of the twins, lived four days before dying of
the same infection threatening her latest offspring.
   Pandas are an endangered species. Fewer than 1,000 have been
counted worldwide. Ling-Ling and Hsing-Hsing are the only giant
pandas on permanent display in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890902-0152 </DOCNO>
