<SECOND>AM-Tropical Weather, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0585,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane Gabrielle Forms in Eastern Atlantic</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to UPDATE with hurricane force increasing to 110 mph;
SUBS 3rd graf and penultimate graf to UPDATE with 10:30 p.m. EDT positions.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gabrielle started out strong and has
surged to the 110 mph mark as it churns westward across the
mid-Atlantic, but it is still far from land, forecasters said
Saturday.
   Gabrielle, the fourth hurricane of the Atlantic season, formed
Thursday off the African coast and quickly grew to hurricane force,
74 mph or more.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT, Gabrielle's center was located near 15.3 north
latitude and 46.3 west longitude, or about 1,100 miles east of the
Lesser Antilles in the West Indies. It was moving west-northwest at
20 mph.
   Additional strengthening is likely as the hurricane moves across
the tropical Atlantic, but forecasters gave the storm only a 10
percent chance of affecting the Lesser Antilles within the next
three days.
   Meanwhile, Tropical Storm Felix has become nearly stationary.
Little movement was expected Saturday, but a gradual shift to the
northwest was expected Sunday.
   Its winds, which dipped below the 39 mph threshold for a named
storm Wednesday, picked up again to 40 mph, forecasters said.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT, the center of Felix remained near 33.5 north
latitude and 40.5 west longitude, or about 640 miles southwest of
the westernmost Azores.
   Neither storm is an immediate threat to land, forecasters said.
</TEXT>
