<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 2356EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-ChamorroProfile     09-02 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chamorro Profile,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housewife Turned Politician Named Presidential Nominee</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raised to be a gracious hostess and
housewife, Violeta Barrios de Chamorro has been thrust upon the
political stage to play a leading role in turbulent Nicaragua.
   She was selected Saturday as the presidential candidate of a
14-party opposition coalition for the Feb. 25 general election.
   Dona Violeta, as she is called by supporters and enemies, is a
strong pro-democracy figure and her lack of formal political
affiliation makes her a unifying symbol for the National Opposition
Union. Coalition members range from communist to conservative
parties.
   Mrs. Chamorro's life resembles that of President Corazon Aquino
of the Philippines: Both women come from wealthy families, married
politically ambitious men and embarked on what they thought would be
a behind-the-scenes life.
   Both became widows, their husbands felled by assassins. Both
picked up their husbands' political torches and continued the work,
with very little preparation, experience or ambition of their own.
   Pedro Joaquin Chamorro was shot down on a Managua street corner
in January 1978, allegedly at the direction of then President
Anastasio Somoza. His death provoked a civil war that culminated
with Somoza's ouster and the Sandinista National Liberation Front
taking power in July 1979.
   Mrs. Chamorro joined the provisional governing junta after Somoza
fled the country, but resigned 10 months later pleading bad health.
Later, she said the leftist Sandinistas had betrayed Nicaraguans by
failing to fulfill their promises of democracy.
   Recently she has said the Sandinistas ``are worse than Somoza.''
   Mrs. Chamorro has remained faithful to her husband's memory and
her first words to the crowd at coalition headquarters Saturday
night were: ``Viva Pedro Joaquin Chamorro!''
   In an interview published by her family's opposition newspaper La
Prensa shortly before the 10th anniversary of the Sandinista
revolution, Mrs. Chamorro said of her husband's death:
   ``It wasn't simply the traumatic change that every woman suffers
when her husband dies. What happened to me was something more
profound. ...
   ``I went from being a simple housewife to being a political
fighter following in my husband's footsteps.''
   La Prensa, a critic of Somoza and then of the Sandinistas, was
shut down for a year then reopened in October 1987 as part of the
Sandinistas' promises for more democracy.
   The Sandinistas accuse Mrs. Chamorro and La Prensa of being
``instruments of imperialism and of the Central Intelligence
Agency,'' and lately of being supporters of Somoza's hated national
guard.
   Yet La Prensa continues to have one of the largest circulations
in the country, and its editorial policy is summed up by Pedro
Joaquin Chamorro's slogan that ``Nicaragua will again be a
republic.''
   The political divisions in Nicaragua are felt even within the
Chamorro family. Of her four children, two are prominent
anti-Sandinistas and the other two are pro-government.
   Mrs. Chamorro's brother-in-law, Xavier Chamorro, is editor of the
pro-government newspaper El Nuevo Diario.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890902-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-89 0125EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Romania-Rights 1stLd-Writethru a0585 09-02 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania-Rights, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0585,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romania Wants Critical U.N. Report Withdrawn From Circulation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs UPDATING with panel vote. Pickup 7th graf,
A Romanian ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania on Friday demanded the United Nations
withdraw from circulation a ``totally incoherent and venomous''
human rights report criticizing the country's communist leadership.
   Western and Third World members of a U.N. human rights panel
instead urged U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar to
investigate the personal situation of the report's author, Dumitru
Mazilu.
   Mazilu has been held incommunicado in Bucharest since 1986, when
he was asked to write a report on human rights and youth for the
U.N. Subcommission on the Prevention of Discrimination and
Protection of Minorities.
   He submitted the report last month and it was published as an
official U.N. document last week.
   Mazilu termed conditions in Romania ``nightmarish.'' He charged
the population was ruled by fear and subject to abject poverty while
the leadership lived in luxury.
   The subcommission voted, 12-4, with two abstentions, that Mazilu
update his report and travel to Geneva to discuss it at the next
annual meeting in 1990.
   A Romanian government official, Gheorghe Chirila, said the report
violated U.N. standards of impartiality and should not have been
published.
   ``It is a totally incoherent, venomous text, deprived of any
meaning'' he said. ``We demand that the document be withdrawn
immediately from circulation.''
   Romanian authorities alleged Mazilu lacked the ``mental
capacity'' to write an objective report. They have said he is too
ill to travel to Geneva to appear before the subcommission.
   ``Dumitru Mazilu continues to be a retired person for reasons of
health. He enjoys a respectable pension. He is free,'' Chirila said.
   But he acknowledged Bucharest has confiscated Mazilu's passport,
suggesting he was ``a citizen whose presence abroad would harm the
Romanian state.''
   In a letter sent with his report, Mazilu said he feared for his
life and for his family.
   Delegates of the 26-member subcommission technically are
independent of their governments. Government delegations and private
groups are allowed to take part in debates as observers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
