<FIRST>r i AM-China-Military     09-02 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Military,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Completes Demobilization of 1 Million Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has completed a four-year drive to
demobilize 1 million soldiers, including 600,000 officers, an
official daily said Saturday.
   The China Daily quoted an official of the Civil Affairs Ministry
as saying it had found civilian jobs for the last 16,000
ex-servicemen and women in the program.
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping in 1985 announced plans to reduce the
People's Liberation Army of 4.2 million by 1 million to help reduce
military spending and make the Red Army a trimmer, more modern
fighting force.
   The troop cutbacks originally were to be made in one year, but
ran into delays, reportedly because of resistance from older
officers reluctant to give up benefits attached to their military
rank.
   The ministry said its basic policy was to return people to the
area from which they were recruited. It said that of 700,000 army
personnel resettled since last year, about 200,000 recruited from
cities and towns found jobs in enterprises and government
institutions. The remainder usually returned to their homes in the
countryside, it said.
   China's military in recent years has suffered budgetary pressures
as the reformist government shifted spending priorities to economic
development areas. Defense industries have been ordered to switch to
producing consumer goods, and money for new weapons systems has been
scarce.
   In 1988, defense received 7.49 percent of the budget, less than
half its share before 1980, and defense spending in actual terms is
expected to fall about 6 percent after inflation in 1989.
   The army played a key role in suppressing the pro-democracy
protests of April-June, however, and observers speculate military
leaders will use that as leverage to push for a bigger defense
budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
