<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials say they are encouraged by
indications that many Latin American democracies are giving the
diplomatic cold shoulder to the new Panamanian government headed by
a loyal follower of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   At least six of the larger Latin American countries have no
ambassador stationed in Panama. But U.S. officials say some have
been ambiguous about the reasons for not being represented.
   U.S. Ambassador Arthur Davis, a political appointee, left Panama
in May and President Bush said Friday that there are no plans to
send him back.
   Bush said no diplomatic contacts are planned with the new
government headed by President Francisco Rodriguez, a friend of
Noriega since high school who served as government comptroller for
seven years. Noriega will continue to serve as the behind-the-scenes
power in Panama.
</TEXT>
